# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The lustrous fiber is traditionally hand-loomed into various indigenous textiles (**abaca cloth** or **medriñaque**) in the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] They are still featured prominently as the traditional material of the barong tagalog, the national male attire of the Philippines, as well as in sheer lace-like fabrics called *nipis* used in various clothing components.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Native abaca textiles also survive into the modern era among various ethnic groups, like the *t'nalak* of the T'boli people and the *dagmay* of the Bagobo people.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abaca is also used in traditional Philippine millinery, as well as for bags, shawls, and other decorative items.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The hatmaking straw made from Manila hemp is called *tagal* or *tagal straw*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The fiber is also exceptionally strong, stronger than hemp and naturally salt-resistant, making it ideal for making twines and ropes (especially for maritime shipping).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] It became a major trade commodity in the colonial era for this reason.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The abaca industry declined sharply in the mid-20th century when abaca plantations were decimated by World War II and plant diseases, as well as the invention of nylon in the 1930s.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Today, abaca is mostly used in a variety of specialized paper products including tea bags, filter paper and banknotes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Manila envelopes and Manila paper derive their name from this fiber.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abaca is classified as a hard fiber, along with coir, henequin and sisal.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abaca is grown as a commercial crop in the Philippines, Ecuador, and Costa Rica.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The abacá plant is stoloniferous, meaning that the plant produces runners or shoots along the ground that then root at each segment.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Cutting and transplanting rooted runners is the primary technique for creating new plants, since seed growth is substantially slower.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá has a "false trunk" or pseudostem about 6–15 inches (15–38 cm) in diameter.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The leaf stalks (petioles) are expanded at the base to form sheaths that are tightly wrapped together to form the pseudostem.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] There are from 12 to 25 leaves, dark green on the top and pale green on the underside, sometimes with large brown patches.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] They are oblong in shape with a deltoid base.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The petioles grow to at least 1 foot (30 cm) in length.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] When the plant is mature, the flower stalk grows up inside the pseudostem.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The male flower has five petals, each about 1.5 inches (3.8 cm) long.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The leaf sheaths contain the valuable fiber.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] After harvesting, the coarse fibers range in length from 6–12 feet (180–370 cm) long.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] They are composed primarily of cellulose, lignin, and pectin.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The fruit, which is inedible and is rarely seen as harvesting occurs before the plant fruits, grows to about 2–3 inches (5.1–7.6 cm) in length and 1 inch (2.5 cm) in diameter.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] It has black turbinate seeds that are 0.167 inches (0.42 cm) in diameter.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The abacá plant belongs to the banana family, Musaceae; it resembles the closely related wild seeded bananas, *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Within the genus *Musa*, it is placed in section *Callimusa* (now including the former section *Australimusa*), members of which have a diploid chromosome number of 2n= 20.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The Philippines, especially the Bicol region in Luzon, has the most abaca genotypes and cultivars.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Genetic analysis using simple sequence repeats (SSR) markers revealed that the Philippines' abaca germplasm is genetically diverse.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abaca genotypes in Luzon had higher genetic diversity than Visayas and Mindanao.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Ninety-five (95) percent was attributed to molecular variance within the population, and only 5% of the molecular variance to variation among populations.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Genetic analysis by Unweighted Pair Group Method with Arithmetic Mean (UPGMA) revealed several clusters irrespective of geographical origin.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Before synthetic textiles came into use, *M. textilis* was a major source of high quality fiber: soft, silky and fine.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Ancestors of the modern abacá are thought to have originated from the eastern Philippines, where there is significant rainfall throughout the year.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Wild varieties of abacá can still be found in the interior forests of the island province of Catanduanes, away from cultivated areas.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Today, Catanduanes has many other modern kinds of abacá which are more competitive.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] For many years, breeders from various research institutions have made the cultivated varieties of Catanduanes even more competitive in local and international markets.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] This results in the optimum production of the island which had a consistent highest production throughout the archipelago.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Europeans first came into contact with Abacá fibre when Ferdinand Magellan landed in the Philippines in 1521, as the natives were already cultivating it and utilizing it in bulk for textiles.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Throughout the Spanish colonial era, it was referred to as "*medriñaque*" cloth.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] By 1897, the Philippines were exporting almost 100,000 tons of abacá, and it was one of the three biggest cash crops, along with tobacco and sugar.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] In fact, from 1850 through the end of the 19th century, sugar or abacá alternated with each other as the biggest export crop of the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] This 19th-century trade was predominantly with the United States and the making of ropes was done mainly in New England, although in time rope-making shifted back to the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] From 1898 to 1946, the United States colonized the Philippines following the Spanish–American War.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] In the early 1900s, a train running from Danao to Argao would transport Philippine abacá from the plantations to Cebu City for export.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The railway system was destroyed during World War II; the abaca continues to be transported to Cebu by road.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Outside the Philippines, abacá was first cultivated on a large scale in Sumatra in 1925 under the Dutch, who had observed its cultivation in the Philippines for cordage since the nineteenth century, followed up by plantings in Central America in 1929 sponsored by the U.S.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] It also was transplanted into India and Guam.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Commercial planting began in 1930 in British North Borneo; at the onset of World War II, the supply from the Philippines was eliminated by the Empire of Japan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Department of Agriculture started production in Panama, Costa Rica, Honduras, and Guatemala.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Today, abacá is produced primarily in the Philippines and Ecuador.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The Philippines produces between 85% and 95% of the world's abacá, and the production employs 1.5 million people.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Production has declined because of virus diseases.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The plant is normally grown in well-drained loamy soil, using rhizomes planted at the start of the rainy season.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] In addition, new plants can be started by seeds.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Growers harvest abacá fields every three to eight months after an initial growth period of 12–25 months.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Harvesting is done by removing the leaf-stems after flowering but before the fruit appears.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The plant loses productivity between 15 and 40 years.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The slopes of volcanoes provide a preferred growing environment.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] When the processing is complete, the bundles of fiber are pale and lustrous with a length of 6–12 feet (1.8–3.7 m).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] In Costa Rica, more modern harvest and drying techniques are being developed to accommodate the very high yields obtained there.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] According to the Philippine Fiber Industry Development Authority, the Philippines provided 87.4% of the world's abacá in 2014, earning the Philippines US$111.33 million.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The demand is still greater than the supply.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The remainder came from Ecuador (12.5%) and Costa Rica (0.1%).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The Bicol region in the Philippines produced 27,885 metric tons of abacá in 2014, the largest of any Philippine region.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The Philippine Rural Development Program (PRDP) and the Department of Agriculture reported that in 2009–2013, Bicol Region had a 39% share of Philippine abacá production of which an overwhelming 92% came from Catanduanes Island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Eastern Visayas, the second largest producer had 24% and the Davao Region, the third largest producer had 11% of the total production.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Around 42 percent of the total abacá fiber shipments from the Philippines went to the United Kingdom in 2014, making it the top importer.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Germany imported 37.1 percent abacá pulp from the Philippines, importing around 7,755 metric tons (MT).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Sales of abacá cordage surged 20 percent in 2014 to a total of 5,093MT from 4,240MT, with the United States holding around 68 percent of the market.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá is vulnerable to a number of pathogens, notably abaca bunchy top virus, abaca bract mosaic virus, and abaca mosaic virus.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Due to its strength, it is a sought after product and is the strongest of the natural fibers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] It is used by the paper industry for such specialty uses such as tea bags, banknotes and decorative papers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] It can be used to make handcrafts such as hats, bags, carpets, clothing and furniture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá fibers were traditionally woven into sturdy textiles and clothing in the Philippines since pre-colonial times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Along with cotton, they were the main source of textile fibers used for clothing in the pre-colonial Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá cloth was often compared to calico in terms of texture and was a major trade commodity in the pre-colonial maritime trade and the Spanish colonial era.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] There are multiple traditional types and names of abaca cloth among the different ethnic groups of the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Undyed plain abacá cloth, woven from fine fibers of abaca, is generally known as *sinamáy* in most of the islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá cloth with a more delicate texture is called *tinampipi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] While especially fine lace-like abacá cloth is called *nipis* or *lupis*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Fine abacá fibers may also be woven with *piña*, silk, or fine cotton to create a fabric called *jusi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Traditional abacá textiles were often dyed in various colors from various natural dyes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] These include blue from indigo (*tarum*, *dagum*, *tayum*, etc.); black from ebony (*knalum* or *batulinao*) leaves; red from noni roots and *sapang*; yellow from turmeric (*kalawag*, *kuning*, etc.); and so on.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] They were often woven into specific patterns, and further ornamented with embroidery, beadwork, and other decorations.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Most clothing made from abacá took the form of the *baro* (also *barú* or *bayú*, literally "shirt" or "clothing"), a simple collar-less shirt or jacket with close-fitting long sleeves worn by both men and women in most ethnic groups in the pre-colonial Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] These were paired with wraparound sarong-like skirts (for both men and women), close-fitting pants, or loincloths (*bahag*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] During the Spanish colonial era, abacá cloth became known as **medriñaque** in Spanish (apparently derived from a native Cebuano name).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] They were exported to other Spanish colonies since the 16th century.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] A waistcoat of a native Quechua man in Peru was recorded as being made of medriñaque as early as 1584.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá cloth also appear in English records, spelled variously as **medrinacks**, **medrianacks**, **medrianackes**, and **medrinacles**, among other names.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] They were used as canvas for sails and for stiffening clothing like skirts, collars, and doublets.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Philippine indigenous tribes still weave abacá-based textiles like *t'nalak*, made by the Tiboli tribe of South Cotabato, and *dagmay*, made by the Bagobo people.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá cloth is found in museum collections around the world, like the Boston Museum of Fine Arts and the Textile Museum of Canada.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] The inner fibers are also used in the making of hats, including the "Manila hats", slippers, hammocks, matting, cordage, ropes, coarse twines, and types of canvas.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Manila rope is a type of rope made from manila hemp.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Manila rope is very durable, flexible, and resistant to salt water damage, allowing its use in rope, hawsers, ships' lines, and fishing nets.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] A 1 inch (2.5 cm) rope can require 4 metric tons (8,800 lb) to break.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Manila rope is still the only material specified for lifeboat falls (the ropes with which a ship's lifeboat is lowered) in the United Kingdom.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Manila ropes shrink when they become wet.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] This effect can be advantageous under certain circumstances, but if it is not a wanted feature, it should be well taken into account.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Since shrinkage is more pronounced the first time the rope becomes wet, new rope is usually immersed into water and put to dry before use so that the shrinkage is less than it would be if the rope had never been wet.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] A major disadvantage in this shrinkage is that many knots made with manila rope became harder and more difficult to untie when wet, thus becoming subject of increased stress.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Manila rope will rot after a period of time when exposed to saltwater.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Manila hemp rope was previously the favoured variety of rope used for executions by hanging, both in the U.K. and USA.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Usually 3⁄4 to 1 inch (19 to 25 mm) diameter, boiled prior to use to take out any overelasticity.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/abacá] Abacá fiber was once used primarily for rope, but this application is now of minor significance.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/aborlan-tagbanwa-language] The following table contains the pronouns found in the Aborlan Tagbanwa language.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/aborlan-tagbanwa-language] Note: some forms are divided between full and short forms.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Being part of the Chamic languages group, Acehnese is the only Austronesian language of the Chamic branch spoken in Indonesia, its closest relatives are the other Chamic languages, which are principally spoken in Vietnam and Cambodia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese belongs to the Malayo-Polynesian branch of Austronesian.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese's closest relatives are the other Chamic languages, which are principally spoken in Vietnam and Cambodia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The distant relative of the Chamic family is the Malayic language family, which includes languages also spoken in Sumatra such as Minangkabau as well as the national language, Indonesian.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Paul Sidwell notes that Acehnese likely has an Austroasiatic substratum.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The first speakers of Cham, which would later become Acehnese, arrived in Sumatra from the Kingdom of Champa, where they would establish a trading outpost and refugee colony.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Further Cham migrations would increase in the late 900s from the fall of Indrapura, as people fled to Angkor, Hainan, Malacca, and Aceh.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese was historically isolated within the regions of Great Aceh and Daya in the northwestern most tip of modern day Aceh, before later spreading into the northern and western coastal regions during the expansion of the Aceh Sultanate under the rule of Ali Mughayat Syah in 1520 through 1524.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The word Aceh was first used by Tomé Pires in 1520, which was spelt as *Achei*, several other variants can be found in European historical records from the 16th to the 18th centuries, such as *Achem* by the Portuguese, *Achin* by the English, and *Atjeh* by the Dutch.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The name *Achinese* and *Achehnese* was used to refer to the language in English, the modern term Acehnese, which is the one used today, was first coined from a 1906 English translation of Snouck Hurgronje's *Studiën over Atjèhsche Klank-en Schriftleer* from 1892.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Literature written in Acehnese was limited, as most literature in Aceh was written in Malay, which was the lingua franca at the time, with the earliest written record of Acehnese is from a manuscript titled *Hikayat Sama'un* (The Story of Syama'un) from 1658 CE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese literature at the time were mostly in the form of poetry, either as *hikayat* or nazam, very few works were in prose, one of which was *Kitab Bakeu Meunan*, a translation of the book *Qawaa'id al-Islaam*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] During the early 1890s, several Dutch publications was made to document and study Acehnese language and literature practises, which mainly uses the Latin script to transcribe the language.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] In 1888, Hendrik August Nicolaas Catenius publishes a trilingual phrase book *Poeĕ Gata Basa Atjeh?
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] (Spreekt gij Atjehsch?)*, 'Do You Speak Acehnese?', containing phrases in Dutch, Malay, and Acehnese.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] In 1891, Snouck Hurgronje was sent to Aceh by the Dutch government, where he collected and study Acehnese and its literacy traditions for seven months.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] In 1892, he would publish *Studiën over Atjèhsche Klank-en Schriftleer*, 'The Study of Acehnese Language and Script', which he explains and presents his Latin orthography to write Acehnese.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese literature stalled after the Indonesian National Revolution due to the political instability at the time and the ongoing Darul Islam rebellion that was taking place in Aceh.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Efforts to promote and standardise Acehnese began in the 1960s, with educational guide and materials being published to teach Acehnese in primary schools, which was taught as a required subject since 1968.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The first encyclopedia in Acehnese, the Acehnese Wikipedia, was launched on August 12, 2009.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] A prose translation of the Quran in Acehnese was published by the Ministry of Religious Affairs on December 13, 2018.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] As of now, there is no newspaper published in Acehnese.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] In 2020, the first Acehnese-language magazine, *Majalah Neurôk*, was launched, initiated by an Acehnese cultural figure, Ayah Panton.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Google Translate added the Acehnese language translation feature on June 27, 2024.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese is primarily spoken in the northern tip of Sumatra, largely concentrated within the northern and western coastal regions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese is spoken by around 2.8 million people (2010 census) within the province of Aceh, Indonesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese is also spoken in neighbouring Malaysia, notably in Kampung Acheh, an ethnic enclave within the region of Yan District, Kedah, where in 2013, 64.4% of Acehnese descendants in the village speaks Acehnese with family.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] An additional fifth dialect, **Daya**, also referred to as **Lamnoe**, spoken in Aceh Jaya, is also recognised as a major dialect, splitting from West Aceh.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Aside from the five major grouping, Acehnese dialects can be further subdivided into ten groups: Pasè, Peusangan, and Matang from the North; Pidie; Bueng, Banda Aceh of Great Aceh; and Daya, Meulabôh, Seunagan, and Tunong of West Coast.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese distinguishes between oral and nasal vowels, though not all phonemes have a nasal equivalent.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The table below shows the Acehnese consonants range of their realizations.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese features a split ergative system.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Intransitives that align with the agent of a transitive verb (Sa) always show agreement by a proclitic (1).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Meanwhile, intransitives that align with the patient of a transitive verb (Sp) may optionally show agreement by an enclitic (2).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Volitionality is the determining factor for whether an intransitive verb is Sa or Sp.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] All Acehnese pronouns and animate, more often than not human, a demonstative is used to refer to something inanimate.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] As with Malay, Acehnese only distinguishes between singular and plural, though they do have a system of respect or politeness.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese has three tiers of respect: familiar or colloquial/informal, standard or neutral, and polite or formal.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese has two forms of "I": *kèe* (familiar) and *ulôn*, 'slave' (polite), *lôn* is a shortened variant of *ulôn*, though they're considered the same pronoun, the form *lôn* is seen more informal.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] *ulôn* and *lôn* may also be written as *ulông* and *lông*, though it's seen as non-standard.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The word *tuwan*, 'lord' may be added at the end of *ulôn* or *lôn* to be more polite, translating as "your slave, O lord" in literal.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] There are three distinct forms of singular "you": *kah* (familiar), *gata* (standard), and *droeneuh* (polite).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] *droeneuh* is formed through combining *droe*, 'self' and the suffix *-neuh*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] *droeneuh* can be used for both polite second and third person, though it's widely used to refer to the second person, to distinguish between the two, *nyan*, 'that' is commonly added when referring to the third person.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Alongside *droeneuh nyan* (polite), there are two other forms of s/he: *jih* (familiar) and *gopnyan* (standard).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The word *gopnyan* is formed through combining *gop*, 'other person' and *nyan*, 'that', translating literally to "that other person".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Another variant of *gopnyan* is *götnyan* through consonant assimilation of final -p and ny /ɲ/.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Combined with demonstratives such as *nyan*, the noun *awak*, 'person' and *ureueng*, 'person' contains a plural sense by its own, and only sometimes acts as singular.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese is written using the Latin script, though no standard spelling has been officially rasterised or agreed upon yet and has largely gone unstandardised.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The *de-facto* standard Latin spelling system (Indonesian: *Ejaan Bahasa Aceh yang Disempurnakan*, lit.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] 'Improved Spelling of the Acehnese Language') is based on the Indonesian spelling system, *Ejaan yang Disempurnakan*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Another popular spelling system, Husaini's Spelling (*Idjaan Husaini*, 'Husaini's Spelling') is also used, popular amongst pro-independence members.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] EBAYD and Husaini are almost the exact same, with the only difference being how they spell the palatal sounds and ⟨ë⟩, Husaini uses tj, dj, nj, j, and sj where EBAYD would use c, j, ny, y, and sy respectively.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The grapheme ⟨ë⟩ is a remnant of Dutch spelling of Acehnese, notably to distinguish between oe /u/ and oë /ɔə̯/, and has mostly dropped out of use outside of the Husaini spelling, it's not officially listed as an official Acehnese glyph in EBAYD and is merged with ⟨e⟩.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The Acehnese alphabet contains 25 letters, using the basic Latin alphabet with 4 additional letters with diacritics: ⟨é⟩, ⟨è⟩, ⟨ô⟩, and ⟨ö⟩.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The diacritics used are based on the spelling system used by Snouck Hurgronje to write Acehnese, which is based on the French alphabet.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Due to its inspiration from Snouck's orthography, the spelling system is also referred to as the Snouck's Spelling System colloquially.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Acehnese additionally uses three digraphs: ⟨eu⟩, ⟨ng⟩, and ⟨ny⟩, as well as the apostrophe mark ⟨’⟩ preceding a vowel to indicate nasality.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The grapheme ⟨k⟩ represents /ʔ/ at the end of syllables, and the grapheme ⟨h⟩ is used to indicate a breathy or murmured consonant when placed directly after one.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Before Dutch contact, the Acehnese modified the Jawi script to write their language, which itself is derived from the Perso-Arabic script.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The adapted writing system called *Jawoe* is akin to a heterogramic writing system, where words are written in Malay or Arabic but read in its Acehnese equivalent.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] In 1966, efforts began to instating the Acehnese language into public use and school curriculums, which arises the need for a standardised spelling of Acehnese.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] This culminated into several seminars between educators and linguists from local universities, which was later perfected into EBAYD in 1980.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] The following texts are excerpts from the official translations of article 1 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights in Acehnese, along with the original declaration in English.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Bandum ureuëng lahé deungon meurdéhka, dan deungon martabat dan hak njang saban.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Ngon akai geuseumiké, ngon haté geumeurasa, bandum geutanjoë lagèë sjèëdara.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Bandum ureueng lahé deungön meurdéka, dan deungön martabat dan hak nyang saban.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] Ngön akai geuseumiké, ngön até geumeurasa, bandum geutanyoe lagèe cèedara.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acehnese-language] "All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] One of the major early human migrations was the maritime Austronesian expansion into the islands of the Indo-Pacific, believed to have begun between at least 5500 and 4000 BP (3500 to 2000 BCE).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They include crops and animals believed to have originated from the Hemudu and Majiabang cultures in the theorized pre-Austronesian homelands in China, as well as other plants and animals believed to have been first domesticated from within Taiwan, maritime Southeast Asia, and New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] These plants are often referred to as "**canoe plants**", especially in the context of the migrations of the Polynesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Domesticated animals and plants introduced during historic times are not included.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The candlenut (*Aleurites moluccanus*) was first domesticated in Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Remains of harvested candlenuts have been recovered from archaeological sites in Timor and Morotai in eastern Indonesia, dated to around 13,000 BP and 11,000 BP respectively.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Archaeological evidence of candlenut cultivation is also found in Neolithic sites of the Toalean culture in southern Sulawesi dated to around 3,700 to 2,300 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Candlenut were widely introduced into the Pacific Islands by early Austronesian voyagers and became naturalized to high volcanic islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Candlenut has a very wide range of uses, and every part of the tree can be harvested.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They were primarily cultivated for the high oil content in their nut kernels.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They were widely used for illumination before the introduction of other light sources, hence the name "candlenut".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The kernels were skewered onto coconut midribs that were then set alight.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Each kernel takes about 3 minutes to burn, so the series could act as a torch.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] This tradition of making candlenut torches exists in both Southeast Asia and Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Candlenut oil extracted from the nuts can also be used directly in lamps.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They can also be used in the production of soaps and ointments, and as preservatives for fishing gear.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Other traditional uses include using the timber for making small canoes and carvings; the sap for varnish and resins; the nut shells for ornamentation (most notably as leis), fish-hooks, toys, and the production of black dyes; the bark for medicine and fiber; and so on.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Some non-toxic varieties are also used as condiments or ingredients in the cuisines of Southeast Asia and the Pacific.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Proto-Malayo-Polynesian ("PMP") word for candlenut is reconstructed as **kamiri*, with modern cognates including Hanunó'o, Iban, and Sundanese *kamiri*; Javanese and Malay *kemiri*; and Tetun *kamii*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, Oceanic words for candlenut are derived instead from Proto-Austronesian **CuSuR*, which became PMP **tuhuR*, originally meaning "string together, as beads", referring to the construction of the candlenut torches.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It became Proto-Eastern-Malayo-Polynesian and Proto-Oceanic **tuRi* which is then reduplicated.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Modern cognates including Fijian, Tongan, Cook Islands Māori, and Niue *tui-tui*; and Hawaiian *kui-kui* or *kukui*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The **giant taro** (*Alocasia macrorrhizos*) was originally domesticated in the Philippines, but early Austronesians in Taiwan obtained it.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] From the Philippines, they spread outwards to the rest of Maritime Southeast Asia and eastward to Oceania where it became one of the staple crops of Pacific Islanders.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Their leaves and stems are also edible if cooked thoroughly, though this is rarely done with giant taro, as it contains higher levels of raphides, which can cause itching.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The reconstructed word for giant taro in Proto-Austronesian is **biRaq*, which became Proto-Oceanic **piRaq*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Oceania, cognates for it include Malayo-Polynesian Wuvulu-Aua *pia*; Oceanic Southeast Solomonic ꞋAreꞌare and Western Oceanic Papuan Tip Motu *hira*; Papuan Tip Kilivila and Central Oceanic Fijian *via*; and Eastern Malayo-Polynesian Hawaiian *pia*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Note that in some cases, cognates have shifted to refer to other types of taro.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The elephant foot yam *Amorphophallus paeoniifolius* is used as food in Maritime Southeast Asia, Mainland Southeast Asia, and South Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its origin and center of domestication were formerly considered to be India, where it is most widely utilized as a food resource in recent times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] From Maritime Southeast Asia, Austronesians also spread even further west into Madagascar and eastwards to coastal New Guinea and Oceania, although they may have spread south into Australia without human intervention.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The elephant foot yam is one of the four main species of *Arecae* cultivated by Austronesians primarily as a source of starch, the others being *Alocasia macrorrhizos*, common taro, and *Cyrtosperma merkusii*, each with multiple cultivated varieties.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Elephant foot yam, however, is the least important among the four and was likely only eaten as a famine food, since it contains more raphides, which cause irritation if not cooked thoroughly.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The practice of chewing areca nuts originated in Maritime Southeast Asia, where the areca palm is native.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The oldest known evidence of areca nut chewing was found in a burial pit in the Duyong Cave site in the Philippines (to which areca palms are native), which dates to around 4,630±250 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its diffusion is closely tied to the Neolithic expansion of the Austronesian peoples.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It was spread to the Indo-Pacific during prehistoric times, reaching Micronesia at 3,500 to 3,000 BP, Near Oceania at 3,400 to 3,000 BP; South India and Sri Lanka by 3,500 BP; Mainland Southeast Asia by 3,000 to 2,500 BP; Northern India by 1500 BP; and Madagascar by 600 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] From India, it was also spread westwards to Persia and the Mediterranean.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It was also previously present in the Lapita culture, based on archaeological remains dated from 3,600 to 2,500 BP, but it was not carried into Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Numerous species of *Artocarpus* are traditionally cultivated or harvested from semi-domesticated or wild populations in Maritime Southeast Asia and Micronesia for food, timber, traditional medicine, and other uses.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The most important species pertaining to the Austronesian expansion however, are *Artocarpus camansi* (breadnut or seeded breadfruit) and *Artocarpus altilis* (breadfruit).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] According to DNA fingerprinting studies, the wild seeded ancestor of *Artocarpus altilis* is the *Artocarpus camansi*, which is native to New Guinea, the Maluku Islands, and the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] *A. camansi* was domesticated and selectively bred in Polynesia, giving rise to the mostly seedless *Artocarpus altilis*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Micronesian breadfruit also show evidence of hybridization with the native *Artocarpus mariannensis*, while most Polynesian and Melanesian cultivars do not.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] This indicates that Micronesia was initially colonized separately from Polynesia and Melanesia through two different migration events which later came into contact with each other in eastern Micronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The reconstructed Proto-Malayo-Polynesian word for breadfruit is **kuluʀ*, which became Proto-Oceanic **kulur* and Proto-Polynesian **kulu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Note that in Māori, *kuru* is only mentioned in tradition, but does not refer to the plant because breadfruit did not survive into New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Also note that it is believed that breadfruit only reached western Maritime Southeast Asia (Java, Sumatra, Malay Peninsula) during the recent centuries, as a result of trade with the Maluku Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Another notable reconstructed word for breadfruit is Proto-Oceanic **maRi* or **mai*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is a common root for words for breadfruit in Micronesia, northern and western New Guinea, the Solomon Islands, the Admiralty Islands, St Matthias Islands, New Caledonia, and parts of the Central Pacific.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The term itself may have originally been for *Artocarpus mariannensis* instead of *Artocarpus altilis*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Cognates include Pohnpeian, Mokil, and Ngatik *māi*; Palauan, Satawal, and Tuvaluan *mai*; Puluwat *mais*; Yapese *maiyah*; and Tongan, Niuean, and Marquesan *mei*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The jackfruit (*Artocarpus heterophyllus*) was domesticated independently in South Asia and Southeast Asia, as evidenced by the fact that the Southeast Asian names for the fruit are not derived from the Sanskrit roots.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It was probably first domesticated by Austronesians in Java or the Malay Peninsula.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The word for jackfruit in Proto-Western-Malayo-Polynesian is reconstructed as **laŋkaq*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Modern cognates include Sundanese, Javanese, Malay, Balinese, and Cebuano *nangka*; Tagalog, Pangasinan, Bikol and Ilocano *langka*; Chamorro *lanka* or *nanka*; Kelabit *nakan*; Wolio *nangke*; Ibaloi *dangka*; and Lun Dayeh *laka*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Note, however, that the fruit was only recently introduced to Guam via Filipino settlers when both were part of the Spanish Empire.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Various species of bamboo (subfamily Bambusoideae) are found throughout Maritime Southeast Asia, Mainland Southeast Asia, East Asia, and South Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Austronesian regions, different types of bamboos have different names, as well as the products made from them.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are used variously as building materials, fishing gear, musical instruments, knives, water and food vessels, and so on.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Bamboo shoots are also a food source in Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A few species of bamboo were carried by Austronesian settlers as they colonized the Pacific islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They include the ʻohe (*Schizostachyum glaucifolium*), the common bamboo (*Bambusa vulgaris*), and the thorny bamboo (*Bambusa bambos*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Reconstructed Proto-Austronesian words that referred to bamboo include **qauR*, **kawayan*, **buluq*, and **betung*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The latter entered Proto-Malayo-Polynesian and Proto-Oceanic as **bitung*, with cognates including Sundanese *awi bitung*; Fijian *bitu*; and Tongan *pitu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Most terms for bamboo in Polynesia, however, originated from Proto-South-Central-Pacific **kofe* (originally from Proto-Polynesian **kofe*, "root").
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Modern cognates include Tongan and Niue *kofe*; Tokelau, Marquesan, Tuamotuan, and Māori *kohe*; Rarotongan *koʻe*; Samoan and Tahitian *ʻofe*; and Hawaiian *ʻohe*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Some names have also shifted to refer to bamboo-like plants; especially in islands where they were not introduced into or did not survive, like in New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Paper mulberry (*Broussonetia papyrifera*), better known as "tapa cloth tree" in the Pacific, originates from subtropical regions in mainland Asia and is one of the best evidence for the mainstream "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis of the Austronesian expansion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Various genetic studies have traced the origins of paper mulberry populations in the Remote Pacific all the way to Taiwan via New Guinea and Sulawesi.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In the Philippines, which was along the expansion path, paper mulberry are mostly descendants of modern introductions in 1935.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is presumed that ancient introductions of paper mulberry went extinct in prehistory due to its replacement with hand-woven fabrics, given that paper mulberry generally only survives under human cultivation.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, its absence in the Philippines further underlines its origins in Taiwan, and not within Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Additionally paper mulberry populations in New Guinea also show genetic inflow from another expansion out of Indochina and South China.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is believed to be the most widely transported fiber crop in prehistory, having been transported along with the full range of the Austronesian expansion, as opposed to most of the other commensal crops in Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Paper mullbery is present in almost every island or island group in Polynesia, including Easter Island and New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Some populations have gone recently extinct after they stopped being cultivated, like in the Cook Islands and Mangareva, although accounts and prepared barkcloth and herbarium specimens of them exist in museum collections gathered by Europeans during the Colonial Period.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They were spread by Polynesians primarily through vegetative propagation with cuttings and root shoots.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They were rarely cultivated from seeds as most plants were harvested prior to flowering, when the stems reach around 1 in (2.5 cm) in diameter, as described by 18th century European accounts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is also unknown if the feral plants reproduced sexually as the plants are dioecious and require both male and female specimens to be present in one island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Paper mulberry is primarily used in the Pacific Islands to make barkcloth (*tapa* in most Polynesian languages).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Barkcloth, can also be made from other members of the mulberry family (Moraceae), including *Ficus* (figs) and *Artocarpus*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Barkcloth was also occasionally made from *Pipturus* nettles, especially in Hawaii.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However the highest quality of barkcloth was from paper mulberry.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Barkcloth was mainly used for clothing among ancient Austronesians and is traditionally made using characteristic stone or wooden beaters which are among the most common artifacts found in Austronesian archaeological sites.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Numerous archaeological remains of barkcloth beaters in southern China has been regarded as evidence that the pre-Taiwan Austronesian homelands were located in the region prior to the southward expansion of the Han Dynasty, particularly around the Pearl River Delta.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The oldest such remains is from the Dingmo Site in Guangxi, dated to around 7,900 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Barkcloth remained an important source of clothing fabrics in pre-colonial Melanesia, Polynesia, and parts of Indonesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, it has been mostly replaced by woven fiber clothing in most of Maritime Southeast Asia and Micronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] There are numerous names for paper mulberry throughout Austronesia, the most general can be reconstructed to Proto-Central Eastern Malayo-Polynesian **malaw*, which also refers to the loincloth and other items of clothing made from paper mulberry bark.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its cognates including Selaru *mal*; Asilulu *mala ai*; Buli *māl*; Numfor *mār*; Tanga, Tolai, and Gedaged *mal*; Rennellese *mago*; Kairiru *myal*; Lusi, Kove, Manam, Gitua, Mota, Niue, Futunan, Samoan, Tuvaluan, Nukuoro, Anuta, and Hawaiian *malo*; and Arosi, Rarotongan, and Māori *maro*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Eastern Polynesia, terms for paper mulberry can also be reconstructed to Proto-Central Eastern-Polynesian **aute*, with cognates including Tahitian and Rarotongan *ʻaute*; Marquesan *ute*; Hawaiian *wauke*; Rapa and Māori *aute*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In most of Polynesia, the term for barkcloth can also be reconstructed from Proto-Nuclear-Polynesian **taba*, meaning "bark", with cognates including Wayan *taba*; Tongan, Samoan, Mangareva, and Rarotongan *tapa*; and Hawaiian *kapa*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Other terms widely used for barkcloth and paper mulberry are derived from the Proto-Polynesian reconstructed word **siapo*, with cognates including Niue, Tongan, and Marquesan *hiapo*; and Samoan and East Futunan *siapo*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The term for barkcloth beater, however, can be reconstructed more extensively back to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **ike*, with cognates including Uma *ike*; Sa'a *iki*; Bauan, Tongan, and East Futunan *ike*; and Samoan and Hawaiian *iʻe*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Mastwood (*Calophyllum inophyllum*) is a widespread timber tree native to tropical Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is notable for its ability to grow to massive sizes in sandy or rocky beaches of island and coastal habitats, as well as its habit of sending out arching large trunks over the water where its seeds are dispersed via the currents.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Due to these characters, mastwood are of particular importance to traditional shipbuilding of the larger Austronesian outrigger ships and were carried with them as they migrated to Oceania and Madagascar.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Other species of the genus *Calophyllum* were also used similarly, like *Calophyllum soulattri*, *Calophyllum peekelii*, and *Calophyllum goniocarpum*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The wood grain of the members of the genus are characteristically interlocked, which make them harder to work with but also makes them stronger as well as being more suitable for carving intricate shapes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They were comparable in importance to how oaks were in European shipbuilding and timber industries.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In many parts of Polynesia, mastwood groves planted in *marae* were considered sacred and abodes of spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Mastwood were also carved into religious objects like *tiki*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also commonly mentioned in the chants and folklore of Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Various parts of the mastwood were integral to the manufacture of outrigger canoes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The large curving limbs were commonly carved into the dugout canoes that formed the keel of the Austronesian outriggers ships.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The strakes, which are attached to the keel by the uniquely Austronesian technique of "sewing" them with a combination of dowels and lashed lugs instead of nails, can also be made from mastwood, but it is more commonly made from other "softer" timber species like *Artocarpus*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Other pieces became masts, outrigger floats, and outrigger spars.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Smaller curving limbs can also be carved into the ribs of the boat.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Aside from shipbuilding, tamanu oil extracted from the fruit kernels were important in Polynesian culture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The oils, as well as poultices made from leaves and flowers, are also commonly used for traditional medicine.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The leaves contain compounds that are poisonous to fish and can be used as fish poison.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The reconstructed Proto-Austronesian word for mastwood is **bitaquR*, with modern cognates including Ilocano *bittáug*; Ifugao *bitául*; Bikol, Cebuano, Maranao, Mansaka and Manobo *bitáʻog* or *bitaʻug*; Nias *bito*; Palauan *btáʻəs*; Wetan *witora*; and Asilulu *hataul*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Western Malayo-Polynesian words for mastwood is derived from the doublet Proto-Austronesian **bintaŋuR*, with cognates including Iban, Malay and Toba Batak *bintangur* or *bentangur*; Tontemboan *wintangor*; and Malagasy *vintáno*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Proto-Oceanic, the reconstructed word is *pitaquR*, with cognates including Nauna *pitɨ*; Loniu *pitow*; Nali *pirow*; Seimat *hita*; Aua *piʻaw*; Pohnpeian *isou*; Rotuman *hefau*; Fijian *vetau*, Tongan *fetaʻu*; Niue, Samoan, and Tuvaluan *fetau*; Nukuoro *hedau*; and Rennellese *hetaʻu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In most of these languages, the name specifically refers to *C. inophyllum*, although in Ifugao, Maranao, Nias, Wetan, and Fijian, the name has become more generalized to large timber trees.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Another set of cognates for *C. inophyllum* in Proto-Oceanic can be reconstructed as **tamanu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its difference from **pitaquR* is unclear, but given the distinction between the terms in the Mussau reflex, **tamanu* probably originally referred to specimens of the tree that grow in island interiors and not on the coastlines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Modern cognates include Mussau, Tongan, Niue, Samoan, and Rarotongan *tamanu*; Fijian *damanu*; and Hawaiian *kamani*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Numerous species of Citrus are native to Maritime Southeast Asia, Mainland Southeast Asia, East Asia, South Asia and Near Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Austronesians cultivated and gathered a variety of citrus for food, medicine and washing with the thorns being used as piercing implements for tattooing.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] *Citrus hystrix*, *Citrus macroptera*, and *Citrus maxima* were also among the canoe plants carried by Austronesian voyagers eastwards into Micronesia and Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Most Polynesian names describing citruses are named *moli* ultimately from Proto-Oceanic **molis*; whether a link to PMP **limaw* is present (albeit indirect) or otherwise is uncertain.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The region between Southwest Asia and Melanesia is the center of origin for coconuts (*Cocos nucifera*), where it shows greatest genetic diversity.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A study in 2011 identified two highly genetically differentiated subpopulations of coconuts, one originating from Maritime Southeast Asia (the Pacific group) and the other from the southern margins of the Indian subcontinent (the Indo-Atlantic group).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Pacific group is the only one to display clear genetic and phenotypic indications that they were domesticated; including dwarf habit, self-pollination, and the round "*niu vai*" fruit morphology with larger endosperm-to-husk ratios.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The distribution of the Pacific coconuts correspond to the regions settled by Austronesian voyagers indicating that its spread was largely the result of human introductions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is most strikingly displayed in Madagascar, an island settled by Austronesian sailors at around 2,000 to 1,500 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The coconut populations in the island show genetic admixture between the two subpopulations indicating that Pacific coconuts were brought by the Austronesian settlers that later interbred with the local Indo-Atlantic coconuts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Most words for "coconut" in Austronesian languages are derived from proto-Malayo-Polynesian **niuʀ*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Modern cognates include Tagalog *niyog*; Chamorro *niyok*; Malay *nyiur* or *nyior*; Tetum *nuu*; Drehu *nu*; Gilbertese *nii*; Hawaiian, Samoan, Tongan, Fijian, and Rapa Nui *niu*; and Malagasy *nio*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Genetic studies of coconuts have also confirmed pre-Columbian populations of coconuts in Panama in South America.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, it is not native and display a genetic bottleneck resulting from a founder effect.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A study in 2008 showed that the coconuts in the Americas are genetically closest related to coconuts in the Philippines, and not to any other nearby coconut populations (including Polynesia).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Such an origin indicates that the coconuts were not introduced naturally, such as by sea currents.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is further strengthened by other similar botanical evidence of contact, like the pre-colonial presence of sweet potato in Oceanian cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] During the colonial era, Pacific coconuts were further introduced to Mexico from the Spanish East Indies via the Manila galleons.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In contrast to the Pacific coconuts, Indo-Atlantic coconuts were largely spread by Arab and Persian traders into the East African coast.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Indo-Atlantic coconuts were also introduced into the Atlantic Ocean by Portuguese ships from their colonies in coastal India and Sri Lanka; first being introduced to coastal West Africa, then onwards into the Caribbean and the east coast of Brazil.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] All of these introductions are within the last few centuries, relatively recent in comparison to the spread of Pacific coconuts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The size and nutrition of Job's tears set it apart from other long-used ancient grains native to this area of Asia, and the well established and recorded use in culinary practices indicate a history at least proportional to that of millet and rice.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Dating of a site in Shizitan has presented dates as early as 28,000 to 18,000 years ago.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Archaeologists have found evidence supporting Job's tears as among the earliest domesticates in Asia, accompanied by millet.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The taro (*Colocasia esculenta*), sometimes referred to as the "true taro", is one of the most ancient cultivated crops and pre-dated the Austronesian expansion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Taro is found widely in tropical and subtropical regions of South Asia, East Asia, Southeast Asia, Papua New Guinea, and northern Australia and is highly polymorphic, making taxonomy and distinction between wild and cultivated types difficult.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is believed that they were domesticated independently multiple times, with authors giving possible locations as New Guinea, Mainland Southeast Asia, and northeastern India, based largely on the assumed native range of the wild plants.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, more recent studies have pointed out that wild taro may have a much larger native distribution than previously believed, and wild breeding types may also likely be indigenous to other parts of Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Archaeological traces of taro exploitation have been recovered from numerous sites pre-dating the Austronesian expansion, though whether these were cultivated or wild types can not be ascertained.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They include the Niah Caves of Borneo, dating to <40,000 BP; Ille Cave of Palawan, dated to at least c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] 11,000 BP; Kuk Swamp of New Guinea, dated to 10,200 to 9,910 cal BP; and Kilu Cave in the Solomon Islands dated to around c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In the case of Kuk Swamp, there is evidence of formalized agriculture emerging by about c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] 10,000 BP, with evidence of cultivated plots, though which plant was cultivated remains unknown.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Regardless, taro were definitely among the cultivated plants of Austronesians as well as preceding populations in Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, their importance in Maritime Southeast Asia had largely been replaced by rice, although they are still planted at the margins of rice paddies in some communities.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They remained a staple in the islands of Melanesia and Polynesia where rice wasn't introduced.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are one of the four species of aroids (taros) cultivated by Austronesians primarily as a source of starchy corms, the others being *Alocasia macrorrhizos*, *Amorphophallus paeoniifolius*, and *Cyrtosperma merkusii*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are the most important and the most preferred among the four, because they were less likely to contain the irritating raphides present in the other plants.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Taro is also identified as one of the staples of Micronesia, from archaeological evidence dating back to the pre-colonial Latte Period (c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] 900 – 1521 AD), indicating that it was also carried by Micronesians when they colonized the islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Due to the unsuitability of the low-lying atoll islands of most of Micronesia, Micronesians innovated by digging pits that could then be filled up with compost suitable for taro cultivation.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Taro pollen and starch residue have also been identified in earlier Lapita sites, dated to around c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] There are numerous terms for taro in the Austronesian languages, both specific and generalized.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The reconstructed Proto-Austronesian term for taro is **cali*, with cognates in Formosan languages including Seediq *sali*, Thao *lhari*; Bunun *tai*; and Amis *tali*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It became **taləs* in Proto-Malayo-Polynesian, which in turn became **talos* or **talo* in Proto-Oceanic.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Modern cognates include Hanunó'o *tálus*; Aborlan Tagbanwa *talis*; Palawan Batak *täläs*; Nias *talõ*; Malay *talas*; Minangkabau *taleh*; Rejang and Sundanese *taleus*; Javanese *tales*; Palauan *dáit*; Rotinese *tale*; and Tetun *talas*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The English name for the plant is itself derived from the Polynesian names.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A red variety of taro also has names derived from reconstructed Proto-Polynesian **pongi*, with cognates including Niue *pongi*; Marquesan *poki*; Hawaiian *poni*; and Māori *pongi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Proto-Western-Malayo-Polynesian, another reconstructed term is **kaladi*, with cognates including Agutaynen, Sabah Bisaya, Iban, Tae', and Wolio *kaladi*; Balinese and Malay *keladi*; and Mongondow *koladi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The beach cordia (*Cordia subcordata*) is an important timber tree with light, finely textured, and somewhat soft wood ideal for carving.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It has no taste and thus was most commonly used for carving utensils, cups, bowls, and other containers; as well as ornamental carvings and musical instruments throughout Austronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The wood is flammable and is commonly used in New Guinea as firewood.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In some cultures, the wood may also be used to build paddles and the keels of the boats.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The seeds can also be eaten, though only as famine food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Other parts can also be used for traditional medicine and for the extraction of dyes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Like *Calophyllum inophyllum*, beach cordia were commonly planted in *marae*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They have cultural and religious significance in some cultures like in Kiribati and the Karimunjawa Islands of Indonesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Hawaii, it was traditional to plant beach cordia around houses and use their bright orange flowers as leis.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Beach cordia, like most trees favored by Austronesians, grow well in sandy, clay, and rocky soil and are a common component in coastal forests and mangrove forests.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Beach cordia was once thought to be an introduced species, but it is now known to be indigenous to most of the islands and coastlines of the Indo-Pacific, propagated naturally by their buoyant seeds.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Nevertheless, they were still deliberately introduced in some islands, with artificial introductions usually found growing with other common trees cultivated by Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Terms for beach cordia is reconstructed to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **kanawa*, with cognates including Iban *kenawa*; Makasarese *kanawa*; Palauan *kəláu*; Gilbertese *kanawa*; Tokelau *kanava*; and Nukuoro *ganava*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Another set of cognates can be reconstructed to Proto-Oceanic **toRu*, with cognates including Nehan *to-tor*; Petats *to-tol*; Fijian, Tongan, and Rarotongan *tou*; and Hawaiian *kou*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] An older reconstructed term is Proto-Austronesian **qaNuNaŋ*, however it is not specific to beach cordia and can refer to other members of the genus with sticky fruits, especially the glue berry (*Cordia dichotoma*) and the lasura (*Cordia myxa*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It also did not reach the Oceanic languages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Cognates include Tsou *həhngə*; Isneg *anúnang*; Hanunó'o and Cebuano *anúnang*; Maranao *nonang*; Manobo *enunang*; Mansaka *anonang*; Malay, Minangkabau, Sasak, Manggarai, and Rembong *nunang*; and Mongondow *onunang*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ti (*Cordyline fruticosa*) is a palm-like plant growing up to 3 to 4 m (9.8 to 13.1 ft) tall with an attractive fan-like and spirally arranged cluster of broadly elongated leaves at the tip of the slender trunk.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It has numerous color variations, ranging from plants with red leaves to green, yellow, and variegated cultivars.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its original native distribution is unknown, but it is believed to be native to the region from Bangladesh, to Mainland Southeast Asia, South China, Taiwan, Maritime Southeast Asia, New Guinea, and Northern Australia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It has the highest morphological diversity in New Guinea and is believed to have been extensively cultivated there.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is commonly misidentified as a "Dracaena", along with members of the genus *Cordyline*, due to past classification systems.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It was carried throughout Oceania by Austronesians, reaching as far as Hawaii, New Zealand, and Easter Island at their furthest extent.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A particularly important type of ti in Polynesia is a large green-leafed cultivar grown for their enlarged edible rhizomes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Unlike the ti populations in Southeast Asia and Near Oceania, this cultivar is almost entirely sterile in the further islands of eastern Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It can only be propagated by cuttings from the stalks or the rhizomes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is speculated that this was the result of deliberate artificial selection, probably because they produce larger and less fibrous rhizomes more suitable for use as food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ti has many uses but it is most notable as one of the most important plants related to the indigenous animist religions of Austronesians, along with fig trees (*Ficus* spp.).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is very widely regarded as having mystical or spiritual powers in various Austronesian (as well as Papuan) cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among a lot of ethnic groups in Austronesia it is regarded as sacred.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Common features include the belief that they can hold souls and thus are useful in healing "soul loss" illnesses and in exorcising against malevolent spirits, their use in ritual attire and ornamentation, and their use as boundary markers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Red and green cultivars also commonly represented dualistic aspects of culture and religion and are used differently in rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Red ti plants commonly symbolize blood, war, and the ties between the living and the dead; while green ti plants commonly symbolize peace and healing.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also widely used for traditional medicine, dye, and ornamentation throughout Austronesia and New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Their ritual uses in Maritime Southeast Asia have largely been obscured by the introduction of Hinduism, Buddhism, Islamic, and Christian religions, but they still persist in certain areas or are coopted for the rituals of the new religions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Polynesia, the leaves of the green-leafed form are used to wrap food, line earth ovens and fermentation pits of breadfruit, and their rhizomes harvested and processed into a sweet molasses-like pulp eaten like candy or used to produce a honey-like liquid used in various sweet treats.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Hawaii, the roots are also mixed with water and fermented into an alcoholic beverage known as *okolehao*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Fibers extracted from leaves are also used in cordage and in making bird traps.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The consumption of ti as food, regarded as a sacred plant and thus was originally taboo, is believed to have been a daring innovation of Polynesian cultures as a response to famine conditions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The lifting of the taboo is believed to be tied to the development of the firewalking ritual.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Philippine anitism, ti were commonly used by *babaylan* (female shamans) when conducting mediumship or healing rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A common belief in Filipino cultures is that the plant has the innate ability to host spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Ifugao people of Northern Luzon, it is planted around terraces and communities to drive away evil spirits as well as mark boundaries of cultivated fields.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The red leaves are believed to be attractive to spirits and is worn during important rituals as part of the headdresses and tucked into armbands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In the past, it was also worn during ceremonial dances called *bangibang*, which was performed by both men and women for warriors who died in battle or through violent means.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also used to decorate ritual objects.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Palaw'an people, it is planted in burial grounds to prevent the dead from becoming malevolent spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Indonesia, red ti are used similarly as in the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Dayak, Sundanese, Kayan, Kenyah, Berawan, Iban and Mongondow people, red ti are used as wards against evil spirits and as boundary markers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also used in rituals like in healing and funerals and are very commonly planted in sacred groves and around shrines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Dayak also extract a natural green dye from ti.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] During healing rituals of the Mentawai people, the life-giving spirit are enticed with songs and offerings to enter ti stems which are then reconciled with the sick person.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Sasak people, green ti leaves are used as part of the offerings to spirits by the *belian* shamans.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Baduy people, green ti represent the body, while red ti represent the soul.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also planted on burial grounds.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Balinese and Karo people, ti plants are planted near village or family shrines in a sacred grove.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Toraja people, red ti plants are used in rituals and as decorations of ritual objects.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are believed to occur in both the material and the spirit worlds (a common belief in Austronesian animism).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In the spirit world, they exist as fins and tails of spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In the material world, they are most useful as guides used to attract the attentions of spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The red leaves are also symbolic of blood and thus of life and vitality.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Ngaju people, ti plants were symbolic of the sacred groves of ancestors.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They were also important in ritual promises dedicated to high gods.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They were regarded as symbolic of the masculine "Tree of Life", in a dichotomy against *Ficus* species which symbolize the feminine "Tree of the Dead".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In New Guinea, ti are commonly planted to indicate land ownership for cultivation and are also planted around ceremonial men's houses.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also used in various rituals and are commonly associated with blood and warfare.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Tsembaga Maring people, they are believed to house "red spirits" (spirits of men who died in battle).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Prior to a highly ritualized (but lethal) warfare over land ownership, they are uprooted and pigs are sacrificed to the spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] After the hostilities, they are re-planted in the new land boundaries depending on the outcome of the fight.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The men involved ritually place their souls into the plants.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The ritual warfare have been suppressed by the Papua New Guinea government, but parts of the rituals still survive.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Ankave people, red ti is part of their creation myth, believed as having arisen from the site of the first murder.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Mendi and Sulka people they are made into dyes used as body paint, and their leaves are used for body adornments and purification rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Nikgini people, the leaves have magical abilities to bring good luck and are used in divination and in decorating ritual objects.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Kapauku people, ti plants are regarded as magical plants and are believed to be spiritual beings themselves.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Unlike other magical plants which are controlled by other spirits, ti plants had their own spirits and are powerful enough to command other spiritual beings.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Red plants are used in white magic rituals, while green plants are used in black magic rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also commonly used in protection and warding rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Baktaman people, red plants are used for initiation rites, while green plants are used for healing.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Ok-speaking peoples also regard ti plants as their collective totem.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Island Melanesia, ti are regarded as sacred by various Austronesian-speaking peoples and are used in rituals for protection, divination, and fertility.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Kwaio people, red ti are associated with feuding and vengeance, while green ti are associated with ancestor spirits, markers of sacred groves, and wards against evil.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Kwaio cultivate these varieties around their communities.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among the Maenge people of New Britain, ti leaves are worn as everyday skirts by women.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The color and size of leaves can vary by personal preference and fashion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] New cultivars with different colors are traded regularly and strands of ti are grown near the village.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Red leaves can only be worn by women past puberty.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ti is also the most important plant in magic and healing rituals of the Maenge.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Some ti cultivars are associated with supernatural spirits and have names and folklore around them.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Vanuatu, *Cordyline* leaves, known locally by the Bislama name *nanggaria*, are worn tucked into a belt in traditional dances like Māʻuluʻulu, with different varieties having particular symbolic meanings.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Cordylines are often planted outside *nakamal* buildings.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Fiji, red ti leaves are used as skirts for dancers and are used in rituals dedicated to the spirits of the dead.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also planted around ceremonial buildings used for initiation rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Micronesia, ti leaves are buried under newly built houses in Pohnpei to ward off malign sorcery.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In instances of an unknown death, shamans in Micronesia communicate with the dead spirit through ti plants, naming various causes of death until the plant trembles.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] There is also archaeological evidence that the rhizomes of the plants were eaten in the past in Guam prior to the Latte Period.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Polynesia, green ti were cultivated widely for food and religious purposes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are commonly planted around homes, in sacred places (including *marae* and *heiau*), and in grave sites.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The leaves are also carried as a charm when traveling and the leaves are used in rituals that communicate with the species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Like in Southeast Asia, they are widely believed to protect against evil spirits and bad luck; as well as having the ability to host spirits of dead people, as well as nature spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In ancient Hawaiʻi the plant was thought to have great spiritual power; only *kahuna* (shamans) and *aliʻi* (chiefs) were able to wear leaves around their necks during certain ritual activities.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ti was sacred to the god of fertility and agriculture Lono, and the goddess of the forest and the hula dance, Laka.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ti leaves were also used to make lei, and to outline borders between properties.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It was also planted at the corners of the home to keep evil spirits away.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] To this day some Hawaiians plant ti near their houses to bring good luck.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The leaves are also used for lava sledding.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A number of leaves are lashed together and people ride down hills on them.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The leaves were also used to make items of clothing including skirts worn in dance performances.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Hawaiian hula skirt is a dense skirt with an opaque layer of at least fifty green leaves and the bottom (top of the leaves) shaved flat.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The Tongan dance dress, the *sisi*, is an apron of about 20 leaves, worn over a *tupenu*, and decorated with some yellow or red leaves.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In New Zealand, certain place names are derived from the use and folklore of ti, like Puketi Forest and Temuka.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The ti plants in Kaingaroa are known as *nga tī whakāwe o Kaingaroa* ("the phantom trees of Kaingaroa"), based on the legend of two women who were turned into ti plants and seemingly follow people traveling through the area.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The reconstructed Proto-Malayo-Polynesian word for ti is **siRi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Cognates include Malagasy *síly*; Palauan *sis*; Ere and Kuruti *siy*; Araki *jihi*; Arosi *diri*; Chuukese *tii-n*; Wuvulu *si* or *ti*; Tongan *sī*; Samoan, Tahitian, and Māori *tī*; and Hawaiian *kī*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The names in some languages have also been applied to the garden crotons (*Codiaeum variegatum*), which similarly have red or yellow leaves.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The cognates of Proto-Western-Malayo-Polynesian **sabaqaŋ*, similarly, have been applied to both garden crotons and ti plants.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In the Philippines, they are also known by names derived from the Proto-Austronesian **kilala*, "to know", due to its use in divination rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Cognates derived from that usage include Tagalog *sagilala*; and Visayan and Bikol *kilála* or *kilaa*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In New Zealand, the terms for ti were also transferred to the native and closely related cabbage tree (*Cordyline australis*), as *tī kōuka*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Yams (*Dioscorea* spp.) is a very large group of plants native throughout tropical and warm temperate regions of the world.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Among these, *D. alata* and *D. esculenta* were the only ones regularly cultivated and eaten, while the rest were usually considered as famine food due to their higher levels of the toxin dioscorine which requires that they be prepared correctly before consumption.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The ube (*Dioscorea alata*), also known as the greater yam or water yam, is one of the most important staple crops in Austronesian cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is the main species cultivated among *Dioscorea*, largely because of its much larger tubers and its ease of processing.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its center of origin is unknown, but archaeological evidence suggests that it was exploited in Maritime Southeast Asia and New Guinea before the Austronesian expansion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ube is believed to be a true cultigen, only known from its cultivated forms.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is a polyploid and is sterile, and thus can not cross bodies of water.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] This restricts its introduction into islands purely by human agency, making them a good indicator of human movement.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Some authors have proposed an origin in Mainland Southeast Asia without evidence, but it shows the greatest phenotypic variability in the Philippines and New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Based on archaeological evidence of early farming plots and plant remains in the Kuk Swamp site, authors have suggested that it was first domesticated in the highlands of New Guinea from around 10,000 BP and spread into Maritime Southeast Asia via the Lapita culture at around c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] 4,000 BP, along with *D. nummularia* and *D. bulbifera*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In turn, *D. esculenta* is believed to have been introduced by the Lapita culture into New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] There is also evidence of an agricultural revolution during this period brought by innovations from contact with Austronesians, including the development of wet cultivation.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, much older remains identified as being probably *D. alata* have also been recovered from the Niah Caves of Borneo (Late Pleistocene, <40,000 BP) and the Ille Cave of Palawan (c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] 11,000 BP), along with remains of the toxic ubi gadong (*D. hispida*) which requires processing before it can be edible.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Although it doesn't prove cultivation, it does show that humans already had the knowledge to exploit starchy plants and that *D. alata* were native to Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Furthermore, it opens the question on whether *D. alata* is a true species or cultivated much older than believed.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ube remains an important crop in Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Particularly in the Philippines where the vividly purple variety is widely used in various traditional and modern desserts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It also remains important in Melanesia, where it is also grown for ceremonial purposes tied to the size of the tubers at harvest time.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its importance in eastern Polynesia and New Zealand, however, has waned after the introduction of other crops, most notably the sweet potato.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The reconstructed Proto-Austronesian word for ube is **qubi*, which became Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **qubi*, and Proto-Oceanic **qupi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It has some of the most recognizable and widespread reflexes in Austronesian languages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In some ethnic groups, the word has been generalized or shifted to mean other types of yams, as well as the sweet potato and cassava.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Other words for ube are also derived from the ancestral names of other species of yam.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The air yam (*Dioscorea bulbifera*), also known as the bitter yam, is one of the lesser cultivated species of yam.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is usually only eaten as famine food in Maritime Southeast Asia, Melanesia, and Polynesia, because of the toxicity of some wild or feral plants when not cooked correctly.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However it is one of only three yams that were carried by Austronesians into Remote Oceania, the others being *D. alata* and *D. nummularia*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The part of the plant harvested are the aerial tubers, as it does not usually produce large underground tubers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It can be reconstructed to Proto-Oceanic as **pwatika* or **pʷatik*, with cognates including Lou *puet*; Lamusong *patik*; Boanaki *posika*; and Kwara'ae *fasia*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, in Lamusong its meaning has shifted to the lesser yam, while in Boanaki, the meaning has shifted to a more generalized term for yams.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It can also be reconstructed to the more generalized Proto-Oceanic **balai*, meaning "wild yam", which became Proto-Micronesian **palai*, with cognates including Rotuman *parai*; Tongan, Niue, and Samoan *palai*; and Rennellese *pagai*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The lesser yam (*Dioscorea esculenta*) is the second most important yam crop among Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Like *D. alata*, it requires minimal processing, unlike the other more bitter yam species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, it has smaller tubers than *D. alata* and is usually spiny.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Like *D. alata* it was introduced to Madagascar and the Comoros by Austronesians, where it spread to the East African coast.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are also a dominant crop in Near Oceania, However, it did not reach to the furthest islands in Polynesia, being absent in Hawaii and New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Starch grains identified to be from the lesser yam have been recovered from archaeological sites of the Lapita culture in Viti Levu, Fiji, dated to around 3,050 to 2,500 cal BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Traces of *D. esculenta* (along with *D. alata*, *D. bulbifera*, *D. nummularia* and *D. pentaphylla*) yams have also been identified from the Mé Auré Cave site in Moindou, New Caledonia, dated to around 2,700 to 1,800 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Remains of *D. esculenta* have also been recovered from archaeological sites in Guam, dated to around 1031 CE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] *D. esculenta* is believed to have been introduced by the Lapita culture into New Guinea at around 4,000 BP, along with agricultural innovations like wet cultivation as well as swidden farming.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In archaeological sites in New Guinea, it is associated with the appearance of high-density populations in the coastal areas.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Terms for lesser yam in Austronesian languages are mostly affixed or two-word forms derived from the **qubi* root for *D. alata*, like Samoan *ufi lei*, *Sundanese* *ubi aung*, Malay *ubi torak*, and Javanese *ubi gemblii*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] A term for lesser yam can be reconstructed in Proto-Philippine as **tugiq*, but its cognates are limited to the island of Luzon, including Ivatan *togi*; Ilocano and Kankana-ey *tugí*; Bontoc and Ifugao *tugi*; and Tagalog *tugiʻ*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] No Proto-Oceanic term can be reconstructed for the lesser yam because it is absent in Remote Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, it can be reconstructed in Proto-Western-Oceanic as **kamisa*, **qamisa*, or **mamisa*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The intoxicating yam (*Dioscorea hispida*), is native to tropical Asia and New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] It is only cultivated minimally in parts of Java.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Elsewhere it is harvested from the wild.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Like *D. bulbifera* it has toxic tubers that need to be prepared correctly before they can be eaten, and thus were only suitable for famine food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] However, it is one of the *Dioscorea* species identified from the Niah Caves archaeological site dating to <40,000 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its names can be reconstructed to Proto-Western-Malayo-Polynesian **gaduŋ*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Its modern cognates in most Western Malayo-Polynesian languages is *gadung* or *gadong* (also *ubi gadung* or *ubi gadong*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The names are also applied to the similarly toxic introduced cassava.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] Ficus is a genus of about 850 species of woody trees, shrubs, vines, epiphytes and hemiepiphytes of the family *Moraceae*, which are collectively known as **fig trees** or **figs**.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] These plants are native to the tropics, with some species extending into the semi-warm temperate zone.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The fruits are also edible for humans, although they are quite tasteless.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] They are usually eaten with sugar and cream in the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The raw leaves are also eaten as a vegetable.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] This is a bush that grows erect with a bare, branchless stem topped with a clump of leaves that give it the appearance of a palm tree (hence the term *pseudopalma* in its name, meaning "false palm").
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The fruit is a dark green fig that grows in pairs, each fruit just over an inch long.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In Luzon, this plant is found in grassland and forest habitats, where it is considered common.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The shoots of this plant are consumed as a type of vegetable, and there are several traditional uses; among these is its use as a remedy for kidney stones, which is obtained from the leaves.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] In the Bicol region, the plant is known as *Lubi-lubi*, and the ojas are cooked in coconut milk.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] This shrub has also been used as a landscaping plant in Hawaii, but it never escaped cultivation or became established in the wild, because the wasp species that pollinates it never reached the islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The root systems of the coloring fig can join to be self-supporting, but the epiphyte usually drops if the host tree dies or rots.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The small rust-brown fruit of the dye fig is the source of a red dye used in traditional fabric making in parts of Oceania and Indonesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p01] The fruit is also edible and an important food source in the low-lying atolls of Micronesia and Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] A study in 2024 based on molecular and morphological data showed that it is a pre-colonial hybrid created in cultivation by Polynesians through a cross between *Hibiscus cooperi* and *Hibiscus kaute*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The parent species were originally from Vanuatu and Tahiti respectively.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The natural distributions of the parents are more than 4,000 km (2,500 miles) apart.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] *H. kaute* was important in Polynesian culture and medicine, which appears to have led to it being taken across the south Pacific in traditional canoes, where it eventually hybridized with *H. cooperi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Noni (*Morinda citrifolia*) is native to Southeast Asia extending to New Guinea and northern Australia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It grows readily in beach and rocky environments.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It has been introduced widely into the Pacific.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] All parts of the plant were used by Austronesians for traditional medicine and timber, but its most common traditional use is for the extraction of red or yellow dyes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The odor of the plant and the fruit was also traditionally believed to repel evil spirits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The fruit is also edible, but is usually only eaten as famine food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] There are several terms for noni that can be reconstructed.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The most widespread is Proto-Central-Eastern Malayo-Polynesian **ñəñu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Cognates include Kapampangan *lino*; Tagalog and Bikol *níno*; Cebuano *ninú*; Gedaged *nanom* or *nonom*; Takia *nom*; Bimanese *nonu*; Tetun *nenu-k*; Leti and Asilulu *nenu*; Leti (Moa) *nienu*; Wetan *neni*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] In some languages the meaning has shifted to mean "small tree" or "shrub" or to the closely related *Morinda umbellata* and *Morinda bracteata*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] In Western Malayo-Polynesian, another term that can be reconstructed is Proto-Western Malayo-Polynesian **baŋkudu*, which may have referred to a different species of *Morinda* originally.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Its cognates including Tagalog and Cebuano *bangkúro*; Agutaynen *bangkoro*; Tausug, Toba Batak, and Balinese *bangkudu*; Sundanese *cangkudu*; Sasak *bengkudu*; Mongondow *bongkudu;* and Malay *mengkudu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] There are also smaller cognate sets, like Proto-Philippine **apatut* for the tree and Proto-Oceanic **gurat* and **kurat* for the red dye produced from the tree.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The earliest domestication of bananas (*Musa* spp.) were initially from naturally occurring parthenocarpic (seedless) individuals of *Musa acuminata banksii* in New Guinea, before the arrival of Austronesian-speakers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Numerous phytoliths of bananas have been recovered from the Kuk Swamp archaeological site and dated to around 10,000 to 6,500 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] From New Guinea, cultivated bananas spread westward into Maritime Southeast Asia through proximity (not migrations).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] They hybridized with other (possibly independently domesticated) subspecies of *Musa acuminata* as well as *Musa balbisiana* in the Philippines, northern New Guinea, and possibly Halmahera.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] These hybridization events produced the triploid cultivars of bananas commonly grown today.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] From Maritime Southeast Asia, they became part of the staple crops of Austronesian peoples and were spread during their voyages and ancient maritime trading routes into Oceania, East Africa, South Asia, and Indochina.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] These ancient introductions resulted in the banana subgroup now known as the "true" plantains, which include the East African Highland bananas and the Pacific plantains (the Iholena and Maoli-Popo'ulu subgroups).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] East African Highland bananas originated from banana populations introduced to Madagascar probably from the region between Java, Borneo, and New Guinea; while Pacific plantains were introduced to the Pacific Islands from either eastern New Guinea or the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] A second wave of introductions later spread bananas to other parts of tropical Asia, particularly Indochina and the Indian subcontinent.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Abacá (*Musa textilis*), also known as Manila Hemp, is grown traditionally for its fiber in the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It was once one of the world's premier fibers, valued for its use in soft, lustrous, and silky fabrics.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It was a major luxury export of the Philippines during the Colonial Era, and was introduced to Hawaii and Central America by Europeans.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It has since been replaced by synthetic fibers like rayon and nylon.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Fe'i bananas (*Musa* × *troglodytarum*), also spelled Fehi or Féi, are banana cultivars unique to Melanesia, the Maluku Islands, and Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Unlike other domesticated banana cultivars which are derived from *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*, fe'i bananas are believed to be hybrids derived from entirely different species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Proposed progenitors of fe'i bananas include *Musa jackeyi*, *Musa lolodensis*, *Musa maclayi*, and *Musa peekelii*, all of which are native to New Guinea and surrounding islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Like other bananas, they were spread eastwards to Polynesia for use as food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] However, they are absent in Maritime Southeast Asia, reaching only as far as the Maluku Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The earliest evidence of use of nutmeg (*Myristica fragrans*) comes in the form of 3,500-year-old potsherd residues from the island of Pulau Ai, one of the Banda Islands in eastern Indonesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The Banda Islands consist of eleven small volcanic islands, and are part of the larger Maluku Islands group.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] These islands were the only source of nutmeg and mace production until the mid-19th century.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It was one of the spices traded over the Austronesian maritime spice trade network since at least 1500 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] In the sixth century AD, nutmeg use spread to India, then further west to Constantinople.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] By the 13th century, Arab traders had pinpointed the origin of nutmeg to the Banda Islands, but kept this location a secret from European traders.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Rice (*Oryza sativa*) is one of the most ancient Austronesian staples, and is likely to have been originally domesticated by their ancestors long before the Austronesian expansion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It remains the main crop plant cultivated in Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] There are two most likely centers of domestication for rice as well as the development of the wetland agriculture technology.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The first, and most likely, is in the lower Yangtze River, believed to be the homelands of early Austronesian speakers and associated with the Kauhuqiao, Hemudu, Majiabang, and Songze cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is characterized by typical Austronesian innovations, including stilt houses, jade carving, and boat technologies.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Their diet were also supplemented by acorns, water chestnuts, foxnuts, and pig domestication.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The second is in the middle Yangtze River, believed to be the homelands of the early Hmong–Mien speakers and associated with the Pengtoushan and Daxi cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Both of these regions were heavily populated and had regular trade contacts with each other, as well as with early Austroasiatic speakers to the west, and early Kra-Dai speakers to the south, facilitating the spread of rice cultivation throughout southern China.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The spread of *japonica* rice cultivation to Southeast Asia started with the migrations of the Austronesian Dapenkeng culture into Taiwan between 5,500 and 4,000 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The Nanguanli site in Taiwan, dated to ca.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] 4,800 BP, has yielded numerous carbonized remains of both rice and millet in waterlogged conditions, indicating intensive wetland rice cultivation and dryland millet cultivation.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] From about 4,000 to 2,500 BP, the Austronesian expansion began, with settlers from Taiwan moving south to colonize Luzon in the Philippines, bringing rice cultivation technologies with them.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] From Luzon, Austronesians rapidly colonized the rest of Maritime Southeast Asia, moving westwards to Borneo, the Malay Peninsula and Sumatra; and southwards to Sulawesi and Java.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] By 2,500 BP, there is evidence of intensive wetland rice agriculture already established in Java and Bali, especially near very fertile volcanic islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] However, rice (as well as dogs and pigs) did not survive the first Austronesian voyages into Micronesia due to the sheer distance of ocean they were crossing.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] These voyagers became the ancestors of the Lapita culture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] By the time they migrated southwards to the Bismarck Archipelago, they had already lost the technology of rice farming, as well as pigs and dogs.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] However, knowledge of rice cultivation is still evident in the way they adapted the wetland agriculture techniques to taro cultivation.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The Lapita culture in Bismarck reestablished trade connections with other Austronesian branches in Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The Lapita culture also came into contact with the non-Austronesian (Papuan) early agriculturists of New Guinea and introduced wetland farming techniques to them.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] In turn, they assimilated their range of indigenous cultivated fruits and tubers, as well as reacquiring domesticated dogs and pigs, before spreading further eastward to Island Melanesia and Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Rice, along with other Southeast Asian food plants, were also later introduced to Madagascar, the Comoros, and the coast of East Africa by around the 1st millennium CE by Austronesian sailors from the Greater Sunda Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Much later Austronesian voyages from Maritime Southeast Asia succeeded in bringing rice to Guam during the Latte Period (1,100 to 300 BP).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Guam is the only island in Oceania where rice was grown in pre-colonial times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Pandanus (*Pandanus* spp.) are very important cultivated plants in the Pacific, second only in importance and pervasiveness to coconuts.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Every part of the plant is utilized, including for food, building materials, traditional medicine, and fiber and weaving materials in various cultures in Austronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The plants (particularly the fragrant flowers) also had spiritual significance among the native animist Austronesian religions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Pandanus were also profoundly crucial in enabling the Austronesian expansion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Their leaves were traditionally woven into mats used in the sails for Austronesian outrigger ships.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Sails allowed Austronesians to embark on long-distance voyaging.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] In some cases, however, they were one-way voyages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The failure of pandanus to establish populations in Easter Island and New Zealand is believed to have isolated their settlements from the rest of Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The word for pandanus in Austronesian languages is derived from Proto-Austronesian **paŋudaN*, which became Proto-Oceanic **padran* and Proto-Polynesian **fara*, the latter two usually referring specifically to *Pandanus tectorius*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Note that among the Formosan languages of Indigenous Taiwanese, the meaning of the words have largely shifted to mean "pineapple", a physically similar non-native European-introduced plant.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] In Māori, as well, the meaning has shifted to *Astelia* spp. and *Phormium tenax* (harakeke), similar plants used for weaving, since pandanus did not survive the voyage into New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Pandanus grow well in island habitats, being very salt-tolerant and easy to propagate, making them ideal plants for early Austronesian sailors.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Like coconuts, they grow predominantly along strandlines, mangrove forests, and other coastal ecosystems.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] They can also be found in the understory of forests in larger islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Others may also be found in highland groves, likely planted by humans.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Both pandanus and coconuts are adapted to withstand the strong winds of the frequent typhoons of the Indo-Pacific.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The greatest center of diversity of *Pandanus* is the western Pacific and Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The genus has around 600 species, but the most important and the most widespread group of species in Austronesian cultures and is the *Pandanus tectorius* complex.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Very old fossils of *Pandanus tectorius* have been recovered from Hawaii, dated to more than 1.2 million years old.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] This indicates that the plants once colonized Hawaii (and likely the rest of the Pacific islands) naturally through their buoyant fruits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] However, useful domesticated varieties were carried by Austronesians from island to island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Especially since wild pandanus have calcium oxalate crystals (raphides) in their fruit tissue.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] They cause itchiness and irritation when eaten raw and thus need to be cooked.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Domesticated varieties which have less raphides (which are also usually less fibrous and more nutritious), were therefore valued .
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is thus considered both native and introduced.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] There are also fossil evidence of pandanus fruits being harvested for food in New Guinea from archaeological sites dated to around 34,000 to 36,000 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Other important species of pandanus utilized by Austronesians include *Pandanus amaryllifolius*, *Pandanus odorifer*, *Pandanus furcatus*, *Pandanus julianettii*, *Pandanus simplex*, *Pandanus utilis*, *Pandanus dubius*, and *Pandanus whitmeeanus*, among many others.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] *Pandanus odorifer* is widespread in the region from western Micronesia, to Maritime Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is possibly a subspecies of *Pandanus tectorius* and they hybridize readily.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] *Pandanus amaryllifolius*, the pandan, is another important species widely used as a spice in the cuisines of Southeast Asia for their vanilla-like fragrant leaves.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Peppers (*Piper*) ancestrally cultivated by Austronesians include the betel (*Piper betle*), cubeb pepper (*Piper cubeba*), kava (*Piper methysticum*), and the Javanese long pepper (*Piper retrofractum*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Many others were also harvested from the wild for medicinal or religious purposes, including *Piper caducibracteum*, *Piper excelsum*, *Piper ornatum*, and *Piper sarmentosum*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Black pepper (*Piper nigrum*) and long pepper (*Piper longum*) were also extensively cultivated in Maritime Southeast Asia after early contact by Austronesian traders with South India and Sri Lanka.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The betel (*Piper betle*) is one of the two plants that comprise the main ingredients of betel chewing, the other being the areca nut (*Areca catechu*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is one of the most ubiquitous practices of the Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is consumed by taking a leaf of betel, wrapping it around an areca nut and some lime (obtained from grinding seashells), and then chewing it for some time.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is a stimulant, inducing slight dizziness followed by euphoria and alertness.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is also highly addictive, damages the teeth and gums, and stains the teeth red.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Based on archaeological, linguistic, and botanical evidence, betel chewing is most strongly associated with Austronesian cultures, despite its widespread adoption by neighboring cultures in prehistoric and historic times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The original range of betel is unknown, but *Areca catechu* is known to be originally native to the Philippines, where it has the greatest morphological diversity as well as the most number of closely related endemic species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is unknown when the two were combined, as areca nut alone can be chewed for its narcotic properties.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] In eastern Indonesia, however, leaves from the wild *Piper caducibracteum* (known as *sirih hutan*) are also harvested and used in place of betel leaves.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The oldest unequivocal evidence of betel chewing is from the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Specifically that of several individuals found in a burial pit in the Duyong Cave site of Palawan island dated to around 4,630±250 BP .
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The dentition of the skeletons are stained, typical of betel chewers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The grave also includes *Anadara* shells used as containers of lime, one of which still contained lime.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Burial sites in Bohol dated to the first millennium CE also show the distinctive reddish stains characteristic of betel chewing.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] From the Philippines, it spread back to Taiwan, as well as onwards to the rest of Austronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It reached Micronesia at around 3,500 to 3,000 BP with the Austronesian voyagers, based on both linguistic and archaeological evidence.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It was also previously present in the Lapita culture, based on archaeological remains from Mussau dated to around 3,600 to 2,500 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] But it did not reach Polynesia further east.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is believed that it stopped in the Solomon Islands due to the replacement of betel chewing with the tradition of kava drinking prepared from the related *Piper methysticum*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It was also diffused into East Africa via the Austronesian settlement of Madagascar and the Comoros by around the 7th century.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The practice also diffused to the cultures the Austronesians had historical contact with.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It reached South Asia by 3,500 BP, through early contact of Austronesian traders from Sumatra, Java, and the Malay Peninsula with the Dravidian-speakers of Sri Lanka and southern India.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] This also coincides with the introduction of Southeast Asian plants like *Santalum album* and *Cocos nucifera*, as well as the adoption of the Austronesian outrigger ship and crab-claw sail technologies by Dravidian-speakers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It Mainland Southeast Asia by 3,000 to 2,500 BP through trade with Borneo, as well as the settlement of the Champa polities in southern Vietnam.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] From there, it was spread northwards into China.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Lastly, it reached Northern India by 500 BP through trade in the Bay of Bengal.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] From there it was spread westwards into Persia and the Mediterranean.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] There are very old claims of betel chewing dating to at least 13,000 BP at the Kuk Swamp site in New Guinea, based on probable *Areca* sp. recovered.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] However, it is now known that these might have been due to modern contamination of sample materials.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Similar claims have also been made at other older sites with *Areca* sp. remains, but none can be conclusively identified as *A. carechu* and their association with betel peppers is tenuous or nonexistent.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] There are numerous cognate sets reconstructible in Austronesian languages relating to various aspects of betel chewing.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Ranging from chewing something without swallowing to equipment used to climb areca nut palms to the betel spittle.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Two other cognate sets reached into Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The first is Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **pu-pulu*, which became Proto-Oceanic **[pu-]pulu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Cognates include Mussau *ulo*; Loniu *pun*; Bipi *pun* or *puepun*; Lukep *ul*; Takia *ful*; Gedaged *fu*; Manam *ulusalaga*; and Bugotu *vu-vulu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The other is Proto-Meso-Melanesian **siqa(r,R)(a)*, with cognates including Kara and Lihir *sie*; Tabar *sia*; Patpatar *sier*; Tolai *ier*; Nehan *hiara*; Petats *sil*; Teop *hia(kuru)*; Tinputz *(ta)sian*; Banoni *siɣana*; and Marovo *hirata*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The cubeb pepper (*Piper cubeba*) are native to Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Like *Piper retrofractum*, however, it was only cultivated extensively in the Greater Sunda Islands for the spice trade.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The Javanese protected the monopoly of the trade by sterilizing the seeds before trading them.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It has a pungent smell, often compared to allspice, quite unlike that of the other culinary peppers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is notable as having reached as far as Greece during ancient times via the Silk Road.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It was a valuable rare spice in Medieval Europe and the Middle East, reputed to have medicinal and magical properties.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Medieval Arab physicians commonly used it for a range of treatments, ranging from treating infertility to poison antidotes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is mentioned in *The Book of One Thousand and One Nights* as well as in the travelogues of Marco Polo.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Its trade waned during the Colonial Era when the Portuguese Empire banned its importation to promote the black pepper produced by its own colonies.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Kawakawa (*Piper excelsum*) is a small tree or shrub endemic to New Zealand and nearby Norfolk Island and Lord Howe Island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It was exploited by Austronesian settlers based on previous knowledge of the kava, as the latter could not survive in the colder climates of New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] The Māori name for the plant, *kawakawa*, is derived from the same etymon as kava, but reduplicated.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is a sacred tree among the Māori people.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] It is seen as a symbol of death, corresponding to the rangiora (*Brachyglottis repanda*) which is the symbol of life.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p02] Boughs of kawakawa are often used in purification rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, kawakawa's resemblance to true kava is only superficial.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Kawakawa roots do not have psychoactive properties.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Instead, kawakawa's primary use is for traditional medicine.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Kava (*Piper methysticum*) is a small tree or shrub believed to have been domesticated in either New Guinea or Vanuatu by Papuans.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is believed to be a domesticated variety of *Piper subbullatum* which is native to New Guinea and the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It was spread by Austronesians after contact into the rest of Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is endemic to Oceania and is not found in other Austronesian groups.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Kava has great cultural and religious significance among Polynesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The roots are pounded and mixed with water then strained through fibers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The resulting cloudy gray liquid is bitter with mildly psychoactive and narcotic properties, with a common effect being numbness around the lips and mouth.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, it is not hallucinogenic or addictive.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The potency of the root depends on the age of the plants.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The leaves and roots can also be chewed directly resulting in a numbing effect and relaxation.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is traditionally consumed both in everyday social interactions and in religious rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Kava reached Hawaii, but it is absent in New Zealand where it can not grow.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Consumption of kava is also believed to be the reason why betel chewing, ubiquitous elsewhere, was lost for Austronesians in Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] According to Lynch (2002), the reconstructed Proto-Polynesian term for the plant, **kava*, was derived from the Proto-Oceanic term **kawaRi* in the sense of a "bitter root" or "potent root [used as fish poison]".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It originally referred to *Zingiber zerumbet*, which was used to make a similar mildly psychoactive bitter drink in Austronesian rituals.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Cognates for **kava* include Pohnpeian *sa-kau*; Tongan, Niue, Rapa Nui, Tuamotuan, and Rarotongan *kava*; Samoan and Marquesan *ʻava*; and Hawaiian *ʻawa*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In some languages, most notably Māori *kawa*, the cognates have come to mean "bitter", "sour", or "acrid" to the taste.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In the Cook Islands, the reduplicated forms of *kawakawa* or *kavakava* are also applied to the unrelated members of the genus *Pittosporum*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] And in other languages like in Futunan, compound terms like *kavakava atua* refer to other species belonging to the genus *Piper*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The reduplication of the base form is indicative of falsehood or likeness, in the sense of "false kava".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The Javanese long pepper (*Piper retrofractum*) is native to Maritime Southeast Asia from the Philippines to Sumatra.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Its northern range also extends to southern China, mainland Southeast Asia, Taiwan, and the Ryukyu Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However it was historically only cultivated in any great extent in the islands of Java and Bali, and surrounding islands, for the spice trade.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Elsewhere it is mostly grown informally in the backyards of houses.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is very similar to the Indian long pepper (*Piper longum*) and is used in the same way in Southeast Asian cuisine.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] There are two centers of domestication for sugarcane (*Saccharum* spp.): one for *Saccharum officinarum* by Papuans in New Guinea and another for *Saccharum sinense* by Austronesians in Taiwan and southern China.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Papuans and Austronesians originally primarily used sugarcane as food for domesticated pigs.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The spread of both *S. officinarum* and *S. sinense* is closely linked to the migrations of the Austronesian peoples.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The second domestication center is mainland southern China and Taiwan where *S. sinense* (though other authors identify it as *S. spontaneum*) was one of the original major crops of the Austronesian peoples from at least 5,500 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Introduction of the sweeter *S. officinarum* may have gradually replaced it throughout its cultivated range in Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] From Maritime Southeast Asia, *S. officinarum* was spread eastward into Polynesia and Micronesia by Austronesian voyagers as a canoe plant by around 3,500 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It was also spread westward and northward by around 3,000 BP to China and India by Austronesian traders, where it further hybridized with *Saccharum sinense* and *Saccharum barberi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] From there it spread further into western Eurasia and the Mediterranean.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The reconstructed word for "sugarcane" in Proto-Austronesian is **CəbuS* or **təbuS*, which became Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **təbuh*, Proto-Oceanic **topu*, and Proto-Polynesian **to*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Malagasy, however, the word for "sugarcane" is *fary*, which is instead derived from Proto-Austronesian **pajey*, meaning "rice".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Several species of Solanum have been utilised as food and medicine by the Austronesian people.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Its name is reconstructed by Robert Blust in Proto-Central–Eastern Malayo-Polynesian as *quRi, and by Malcolm Ross as Proto-Oceanic *quRis.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It remains widely cultivated in Polynesia, where it is generally known under the names *vī* or *wī,* and variants thereof.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is also known as *uli*, *uri*, or *kuli* in various languages in Melanesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In the Philippines, it is known as *hevi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Trees in the genus *Syzygium* contain some of the most important fruit trees among Austronesian peoples.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Two species are also important sources of spice: the clove tree (*Syzygium aromaticum*) and Indonesian bay leaf (*Syzygium polyanthum*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Until the colonial era, cloves only grew on a few islands in the Moluccas (historically called the Spice Islands), including Bacan, Makian, Moti, Ternate, and Tidore.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] One clove tree named *Afo* that experts believe is the oldest in the world on Ternate may be 350–400 years old.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Cloves were first traded by the Austronesian peoples in the Austronesian maritime trade network (which began around 1500 BC, later becoming the Maritime Silk Road and part of the Spice Trade).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The first notable example of modern clove farming developed on the east coast of Madagascar, and is cultivated in three separate ways, a monoculture, agricultural parklands, and agroforestry systems.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The mountain apple (*Syzygium malaccense*) along with the closely related species like the water apple (*Syzygium aqueum*) and the Java apple (*Syzygium samarangense*), are native throughout Maritime Southeast Asia and were cultivated since prehistory.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They were all carried by Austronesians into the Pacific and planted deliberately.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They were valued primarily for their abundant edible fruits.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is also used for timber (usually for building houses) and parts of the trees are used in traditional medicine.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The attractive flowers are also worn as personal hair adornments and in making leis.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They were primarily propagated through cuttings by Melanesians and Polynesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The groves of mountain apples found in the Pacific are often remnants of ancient plantings, as the seeds of the fruits are too large to be dispersed by the native birds.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Related species endemic to the Pacific Islands were also utilized similarly, like *Syzygium corynocarpum* and *Syzygium neurocalyx*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] There numerous names for mountain apples in Austronesian languages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In the Philippines, the terms can be reconstructed to Proto-Philippine **makúpa*, with cognates including Ilocano, Aklanon, and Cebuano *makúpa*; and Tagalog and Bikol *makópa*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Oceania, there are several cognate sets reconstructible for mountain apples and related species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Four of which are **pokaq*, **marisapa*, **sakau* and **cay*, with limited reflexes and may have originally referred to other species.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The most widespread cognate set, however, can be reconstructed to Proto-Oceanic **kapika*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Māori, the names have shifted to *Metrosideros fulgens*, which have similar-looking flowers, as Malay apples did not survive into New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Polynesian arrowroot (*Tacca leontopetaloides*) is another ancient Austronesian root crop closely related to yams.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is originally native to Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It was introduced throughout the entire range of the Austronesian expansion, including Micronesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Polynesian arrowroot have been identified as among the cultivated crops in Lapita sites in Palau, dating back to 3,000 to 2,000 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It was also introduced to Sri Lanka, southern India, and possibly also Australia through trade and contact.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Polynesian arrowroot was a minor staple among Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The roots are bitter if not prepared properly, thus it was only cultivated as a secondary crop to staples like *Dioscorea alata* and *Colocasia esculenta*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Its importance increased for settlers in the Pacific Islands, where food plants were scarcer, and it was introduced to virtually all the inhabited islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They were valued for their ability to grow in low islands and atolls, and were often the staple crops in islands with these conditions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In larger islands, they were usually allowed to grow feral and were useful only as famine food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Several cultivars have been developed in Polynesia due to the thousands of years of artificial selection.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The starch extracted from the root with traditional methods can last for a very long time, and thus can be stored or traded.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The starch can be cooked in leaves to make starchy puddings.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Due to the introduction of modern crops, it is rarely cultivated today.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The names for Polynesian arrowroot in Austronesian languages reflect its secondary importance as a crop.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They are often reassignments from names of other starch crops, rather than specifically being for Polynesian arrowroot.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Usually, the names of Polynesian arrowroot are transferred from the names of the sago palms (*Metroxylon sagu*), giant swamp taros (*Cyrtosperma merkusii*), and fermented breadfruit (*Artocarpus altilis*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Derivations from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **sagu* ("sago palm"), include Chamorro and Toba Batak *sagu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Derivations from Proto-Polynesian **mā* ("fermented breadfruit"), included Tongan *māhoaʻa*; Tokelauan *mahoā*; Anutan *maoa*; East Futunan *māsoʻā*; Samoan *māsoā*; and Tuvaluan *māsoa*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Derivations from Proto-Polynesian **bulaka* (giant swamp taro) include Patpatar and Tolai *pulaka*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Derivations from Proto-Austronesian **biRaq* (giant taro) include Äiwoo *(to)piya*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] And finally, derivations from Proto-Oceanic *Rabia* (sago) include Bauan *yabia*; and Pileni, Rarotongan, and Hawaiian *pia*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Sea hibiscus (*Talipariti tiliaceum*) is a common tree in beaches in the tropical Indo-Pacific.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is widely used by Austronesian peoples for timber and fiber.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It has several subspecies, two of which are endemic to the Philippines and Sulawesi, with the rest widespread throughout its range or native to large regions of Southeast Asia and the Pacific.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The seeds remain viable for months after floating in the sea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, no remains of beach hibiscus have been recovered from Polynesia prior to the Austronesian arrival, making it clear that they were introduced by Austronesian voyagers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The wood is soft and not very durable, so it is mostly only used for products like carvings, spears, bowls, and bracelets.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, it is also resistant to saltwater and thus can be used to make small canoes and outriggers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The wood is also preferred for fire making by friction.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The fiber extracted from the bark is widely used to make cordage and for caulking.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The bark is also used in the production of tempeh in Southeast Asia, and kava drinks in Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The attractive flowers are commonly made into leis in Hawaii.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The terms for beach hibiscus can be reconstructed to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **baRu*, which became Proto-Oceanic **paRu* and Proto-Micronesian **kili-fau*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In addition, there are numerous terms relating to the use of sea hibiscus for cordage and fiber in various Austronesian languages which can be traced back to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian or Proto-Austronesian, like **Calis*, "rope".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The Pacific rosewood (*Thespesia populnea*) is closely related to beach hibiscus.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They are similar in appearance and grow in the same habitats, thus they are commonly confused with each other.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is also used similarly among Austronesian cultures, being one of the main sources of bast fibers for the production of cordage and wood for Austronesian outrigger ships and carving.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Pacific rosewood is native to the Old World tropics.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Like beach hibiscus, the seeds remain viable for months after floating in the sea but no remains of *T. populnea* have been recovered from Polynesia prior to the Austronesian expansion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Thus it is regarded as deliberate introductions by Austronesian settlers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The trees were regarded as sacred in Polynesian culture, and were commonly planted in *marae* sites along with trees like *Ficus*, *Fagraea berteroana*, *Casuarina equisetifolia* and *Calophyllum inophyllum*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The terms for Pacific rosewood can be reconstructed to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **balu*, with cognates including Itbayaten *valu*; Malagasy *válo*; Simeulue *falu*; Ngela *valu*; Arosi *haru*; and Lonwolwol *bal*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Another term which extends to Oceanic is Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **banaRu* with cognates including Hanunó'o *banagu*; Tolai *banar*; Patpatar *banaro*; Mota *vanau*; and Pohnpeian *pana*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Eastern Polynesia, most modern names can be reconstructed back to Proto-Eastern Oceanic **milo*, with cognates including Tongan, Niue, Samoan, and Hawaiian *milo*; Rapa Nui, Tahitan, Tuamotuan, and Māori *miro*; and Marquesan *miʻo*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In some islands, the names have shifted to refer to trees that are used similarly, like *Prumnopitys ferruginea* in New Zealand and *Sophora toromiro* in Easter Island.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Gingers (family Zingiberaceae) were cultivated extensively by Austronesians for food, medicine, weaving materials, and for religious purposes.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The most commonly cultivated species include the lengkuas (*Alpinia galanga*), fingerroot (*Boesenbergia rotunda*), turmeric (*Curcuma longa*), torch ginger (*Etlingera elatior*), and ginger (*Zingiber officinale*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The lengkuas (*Alpinia galanga*) is native to Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Its original center of cultivation during the spice trade was Java, and today it is still cultivated extensively in Maritime Southeast Asia, most notably in the Greater Sunda Islands and the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is valued for its use in food and for traditional medicine and is regarded as being superior to ginger.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It has a pungent smell reminiscent of black pepper.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The red and white cultivars are often used differently, with the red cultivars being primarily medicinal, and the white cultivars being primarily a spice.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Lengkuas is also the source of the leaves used to make *nanel* among the Kavalan people of Taiwan, a rolled leaf instrument used as a traditional children's toy common among Austronesian cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Some of the names have become generalized and are also applied to other species of *Alpinia* as well as for *Curcuma zedoaria*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] There is strong evidence that turmeric (*Curcuma longa*) as well as the related white turmeric (*Curcuma zedoaria*) were independently domesticated by Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Turmeric has a very widespread distribution and names that pre-date contact with India, being found among all Austronesian regions with the exception of Taiwan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, it was seemingly originally domesticated for the production of dyes, eventually contributing to the words for "yellow" and "red" in various Austronesian languages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The plant is important in the Philippines and Indonesia as a traditional dye for clothing and food coloring.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It was particularly valued for coloring food offerings to spirits as well as body painting in religious rituals or social ceremonies.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is also used as a spice, as medicine and as food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Similar uses are also found in the other islands settled by Austronesians, including Madagascar and the Comoros in East Africa.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Micronesia, it was a valuable trade item acquired from Yap.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Polynesia and Melanesia, they are primarily used as body paint in rituals or as a cosmetic.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The latter regions have been isolated for centuries from the rest of Maritime Southeast Asia prior to European contact.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] There are two main cognate sets for *C. longa* and *C. zedoaria* (both of which produce yellow dye) in Austronesian languages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The first is reconstructed as Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **kunij* which originally referred to turmeric.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Its cognates include Ilocano, Kankana-ey, and Isneg *kúnig*; Bontoc *kúnəg*; Ifugao *ūnig*; Casiguran Dumagat *kuneg*; Iban and Malay *kunyit*; Toba Batak *hunik*; Javanese *kunir*; Sangir and Tae' *kuniʻ*; Uma *kuni*; Rembong *kunis*; Ngadha *wuné*; and Manggarai *wunis*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Malagasy and Betsimisaraka, the cognates *hónitra* and *húnitra* have shifted meaning to a different plant used to make red dye.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Other cognates like Ilocano *kimmúnig*; Uma *mo-kuni*, and Tae' *pakuniran* all mean "yellow" or "to dye something yellow".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The other cognate set is derived from reconstructed Proto-Western-Malayo-Polynesian *temu, and originally meant *C. zedoaria* which was used primarily as a spice.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It also sometimes shifted to ginger and other ginger-like plants used for cooking (rather than dye production).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Its cognates include Kapampangan and Balinese *tamu*; Tagalog *támo*; Visayan *tamangyan*; Bukidnon *tamohilang*; Bikol *tamahilan* or *tamaylan*; Malay, Javanese, and Sasak *temu*; Makasarese *tammu*; and Malagasy *tamutamu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In other Austronesian languages in East Africa, however, the other cognates mean "yellow", including Comorian Shibushi and Antemoro *tamutamu*; and Antambahoaka and Antankarana *manamutamu*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Proto-Oceanic, there are two main cognate sets derived from reconstructed **aŋo* and **deŋ(w)a*, both are unrelated to the Proto-Malayo-Polynesian etymons.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The latter probably originally applied to the dye produced from turmeric, while the former referred originally to the plant itself.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Cognates include Fijian *cango*; and Tongan and Rennellese *ango*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Cognates that mean "yellow" also exist in numerous other languages in Near Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Ginger (*Zingiber officinale*) is native to Maritime Southeast Asia and was probably originally domesticated by Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It is an ancient and ubiquitous crop among Austronesians, reaching all the way to Remote Oceania and Madagascar.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Aside from being used for cuisine, ginger appears to have significant religious and medicinal roles in early Austronesian cultures, based on the glosses it acquired.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Ginger were chewed by shamans and spat out intermittently in rituals for healing, warding, and blessing ships.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Proto-Austronesian, the terms for ginger can be reconstructed to **dukduk*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] With cognates including Pazeh *dukuduk*; Thao *suksuk*; Tsou *cucʻu*; and Saaroa *suusuku*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] This was replaced by **laqia* in languages south of Taiwan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The terms for ginger beyond Taiwan can be reconstructed to Proto-Malayo-Polynesian **laqia*, which became Proto-Oceanic **laqia* and Proto-Central Polynesian **laya*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In Oceanic languages, cognates include Lou and Kairiru *lei*; Penchal *lai*; Ahus and Kurti *liy*; Drehet *lip*; Lindrow *ley*; Mussau and Wuvulu, Neham *laia*; Tanga *lae*; Lakalai *la lahia*; Gitua *laea*; Wedau *naia*; 'Āre'āre and Arosi *ria*; Sa'a *lie*; and Fijian *cango laya*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Bitter ginger (*Zingiber zerumbet*) is native to tropical Asia and Australasia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Like the ginger, was carried by Austronesian settlers all the way to Remote Oceania during prehistoric times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Thus it is likely that it was originally domesticated by Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Remains of bitter ginger have also been identified from the Kuk Swamp archaeological site in New Guinea at the Phase 1 layers dated to 10,220 to 9,910 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, whether they were cultivated or simply exploited from the wild is unknown.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Bitter ginger is primarily used for traditional medicine.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] It also has mildly psychoactive properties when consumed, and thus had ritual importance among early Austronesian cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Some reflexes of it still refer to bitter ginger, including Sissano *(una)kaw*; Gapapaiwa *kaware*; Tikopia, Anutan, and Wallisian *kava-pui*; Samoan *ʻava-pui*; Tahitian *ava-puhi*; and Hawaiian *ʻawa-puhi*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Other reflexes also refer to other members of the genus *Piper*, to fish poison, or as words to describe bitter, sour, or acrid flavors.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In non-Oceanic languages, terms for bitter ginger can be reconstructed to Proto-Western Malayo-Polynesian **lampuyaŋ*, with cognates including Cebuano and Ngaju Dayak *lampuyang*; Javanese *lempuyang*; and Malay *lempoyang*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Water buffaloes are essential work animals in Austronesian paddy field agriculture and were carried along with rice to Maritime Southeast Asia from mainland Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Early introductions were specifically of the swamp-type water buffaloes (like the carabao), although they are increasingly being replaced by river-type water buffaloes imported from South Asia in recent times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The earliest remains of water buffaloes in Maritime Southeast Asia with signs of domestication comes from multiple fragmentary skeletal remains recovered from the upper layers of the Neolithic Nagsabaran site, part of the Lal-lo and Gattaran Shell Middens (~2200 BCE to 400 CE) of northern Luzon.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Most of the remains consisted of skull fragments, almost all of which have cut marks indicating they were butchered.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The remains are associated with red slipped pottery, spindle whorls, stone adzes, and jade bracelets; which have strong affinities to similar artifacts from Neolithic Austronesian archeological sites in Taiwan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Based on the radiocarbon date of the layer in which the oldest fragments were found, water buffaloes were first introduced to the Philippines by at least 500 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The English term "carabao" is borrowed from the Spanish word *carabao*, which is derived from Eastern Visayan (likely Waray) *karabàw*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Cognates include Cebuano *kábaw*, Tagalog *kalabáw*, Kavalan *qabaw*, Minangkabau *kabau*, Malay/Indonesian *kerbau*, and Javanese *kebo*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] These Austronesian terms appear to be loanwords from the Austroasiatic languages and likely derives from a secondary pre-colonial introduction of water buffaloes into Maritime Southeast Asia via western Indonesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, it is also clear that Austronesians already had ancient terms for the carabao, reconstructed as Proto-Austronesian *qaNuaŋ.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Cognates include Papora *loan*, Thao *qnuwan*, Siraya *luang*, Rukai *nwange*, Ilocano *nuang*, Tagalog *anwang* or *anowang*, Kankanaey *nuang*, Isneg *nuang*, Itawis *nwang*, Bontoc *nuwang*, Ifugao *nuwang*, and Aklanon *anwang*.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Cognates survive into Sulawesi, but the terms there apply to the related anoa.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Similarly, Hanunó'o *anwang* also refers to the tamaraw of Mindoro, rather than the carabao.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] These terms spread southwards from Taiwan, indicating that domesticated carabaos were carried partially into the Philippines during the Austronesian expansion, but didn't move further south into the rest of Maritime Southeast Asia until the second introduction from Mainland Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Other native names for carabaos include *damulag* in Tagalog, Bikol, and Kapampangan; *dueg* in Pangasinan; and *pagad* in Ivatan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Bali cattle were domesticated in Bali from the wild banteng around 3500 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Dogs were primarily valued for their social functions in various Austronesian cultures, acting as companions and pets.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They were also trained to be hunting or guard dogs.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Ornaments made from dog fur, teeth, and bones are found in archaeological sites throughout Austronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] These could be traded as commodities, along with dog pups.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Dogs were also sometimes eaten, but this varies by culture, with most groups refusing to eat dogs, while in others they were apparently a main food source.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In 2020, an mDNA study of ancient dog fossils from the Yellow River and Yangtze River basins of southern China showed that most of the ancient dogs fell within haplogroup A1b, as do the Australian dingoes and the pre-colonial dogs of the Pacific, but in low frequency in China today.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The specimen from the Tianluoshan archaeological site (Hemudu culture, pre-Austronesians), Zhejiang province dates to 7,000 YBP and is basal to the entire lineage.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The dogs belonging to this haplogroup were once widely distributed in southern China, then dispersed through Southeast Asia into New Guinea and Oceania, but were replaced in China 2,000 YBP by dogs of other lineages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The origins of the dog (*Canis lupus familiaris*) population in Maritime Southeast Asia, Australia, and New Guinea are contentious, with various authors proposing origins from either Mainland Southeast Asia, Taiwan, or both at different times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] These introduction events have been linked to the origin of the Australian dingoes and the New Guinea singing dogs, both of which are clearly descended from domesticated dogs.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The specifics of which population they are derived from, who introduced them, and whether they come from a common ancestor, however, still do not have a consensus.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Regardless, most authors agree that there were at least two introduction events.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] One arriving with Paleolithic maritime hunter-gatherers by at least 10,000 to 5,000 BP, and another arriving with later Neolithic seafaring migrations of farming and trading Austronesian peoples (via Taiwan) by at least by at least 5,000 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The Neolithic dogs are differentiated from previous populations in having the ability to digest starch, indicating that they accompanied humans who cultivated cereal crops.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The Neolithic introductions are believed to have partially replaced the original introductions and became the ancestors of the modern village dogs of Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Austronesian dogs like the Taiwan dog were deeply valued as hunting companions (particularly for wild boar).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] In the Philippines, dog remains have been found buried near or beside human graves in archaeological sites.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The oldest archaeological remains of dogs in Maritime Southeast Asia and Oceania is a dog burial in Timor and dingo remains in Australia, both of which are dated to around 3,500 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The former are believed to have been part of the second wave and the latter from the first wave.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] From Maritime Southeast Asia, they were carried by Austronesian voyagers into Near Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, unlike in Maritime Southeast Asia, dogs lost their economic importance as hunting animals among Austronesians that reached the smaller islands in Melanesia and Polynesia, which had no populations of wild boar or other large mammals that could be hunted.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They became a competitor for limited food resources and thus were themselves eaten.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The Austronesian domesticated dogs originally carried by the Lapita Culture migrations were eaten to extinction in many islands since ancient times.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Thus Austronesian dogs were "lost" during the early colonization of Near Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] This caused a marked discontinuity in the genes of domesticated dogs, as well as the terms for "dog", among Austronesians in the Pacific Islands and Island Melanesia, in comparison to other Austronesian regions in Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] However, dogs were later reintroduced from neighboring Papuan groups and were subsequently carried eastward into Polynesia by post-Lapita Austronesian migrations, reaching as far as Hawaii and New Zealand.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Though these dogs were treated as food animals, rather than hunting companions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Genetic studies have confirmed this, showing that Polynesian dogs are descended from the first wave of dog introductions and are not related to the dogs originating from Taiwan and the Philippines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Dogs were historically eaten in Tahiti and other islands of Polynesia, including Hawaii at the time of first European contact.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] James Cook, when first visiting Tahiti in 1769, recorded in his journal, "few were there of us but what allow'd that a South Sea Dog was next to an English Lamb, one thing in their favour is that they live entirely upon Vegetables".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Calvin Schwabe reported in 1979 that dog was widely eaten in Hawaii and considered to be of higher quality than pork or chicken.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] When Hawaiians first encountered early British and American explorers, they were at a loss to explain the visitors' attitudes about dog meat.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The Hawaiians raised both dogs and pigs as pets and for food.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] They could not understand why their British and American visitors only found the pig suitable for consumption.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] This practice seems to have died out, along with the native Hawaiian breed of dog, the unique Hawaiian Poi Dog, which was primarily used for this purpose.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Dogs were not introduced to Madagascar by Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] A genetic study by Ardalan *et al.* (2015) revealed that the dog population in Madagascar were all derived solely from African dog populations and did not come from Southeast Asian dog populations.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] This aberrant origin is also reflected in the Malagasy languages, where the terms for "dog" originate entirely from African Bantu languages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Given the inferred importance of dogs to Austronesian voyagers, the authors proposed that the Austronesian settlers in Madagascar may have initially brought dogs, but they either died or were used as food sources during the journey.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Another possibility is that the limited initial number of Austronesian dogs may have simply resulted in their genes getting swamped by the influx of a far larger population of dogs from Africa.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Junglefowl were one of the three main animals (along with domesticated pigs and dogs) carried by early Austronesian peoples from Maritime Southeast Asia in their voyages to the islands of Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Pigs were one of the three main animals (along with domesticated chickens and dogs) carried by early Austronesian peoples from Maritime Southeast Asia in their voyages to the islands of Oceania.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Other species of pigs (*Sus celebensis*, *Sus barbatus*, *Sus cebifrons*, and *Sus verrucosus*), also spread much earlier from Mainland Southeast Asia to Maritime Southeast Asia west of the Wallace Line, via natural means or via earlier (non-Austronesian) hunter-gatherer groups.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Many of these endemic pigs later interbred and hybridized with the *Sus scrofa* carried by Austronesians who settled these islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] But pigs in Near and Remote Oceania don't exhibit admixture, indicating that the first wave of Austronesian migrations via the Philippines that carried pigs likely did not mix with local preexisting human groups in Maritime Southeast Asia until much later.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The following rodent species are common in mainland Southeast Asia, but are restricted to areas of wet rice cultivation in western Indonesia (Sumatra and Java).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] The following two rodents are native to South Asia and also present in western Indonesian rice fields, so their presence in Maritime Southeast Asia cannot easily be explained by Austronesian expansions, but perhaps instead by the Indian Ocean trade.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] This rat originated on the island of Flores in Indonesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] Polynesians accidentally or deliberately introduced it to the islands they settled.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia-p03] This rat has been implicated in many of the extinctions of native birds and insects in the Pacific; these species had evolved in the absence of mammals and could not cope with predation by the rat.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They also include indigenous ethnic minorities in Vietnam, Cambodia, Myanmar, Thailand, Hainan, and the Torres Strait Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The nations and territories predominantly populated by Austronesian-speaking peoples are sometimes known collectively as **Austronesia**.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The group originated from a prehistoric seaborne migration, known as the Austronesian expansion, from Taiwan, circa 3000 to 1500 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Austronesians reached the Batanes Islands in the northernmost Philippines by around 2200 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They used sails some time before 2000 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In conjunction with their use of other maritime technologies (notably catamarans, outrigger boats, lashed-lug boats, and the crab claw sail), this enabled phases of rapid dispersal into the islands of the Indo-Pacific, culminating in the settlement of New Zealand c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] During the initial part of the migrations, they encountered and assimilated (or were assimilated by) the Paleolithic populations that had migrated earlier into Maritime Southeast Asia and New Guinea.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They reached as far as Easter Island to the east, Madagascar to the west, and New Zealand to the south.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] At the furthest extent, they might have also reached the Americas.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Aside from language, Austronesian peoples widely share cultural characteristics, including such traditions and traditional technologies as lashed-lug shipbuilding, tattooing, stilt houses, jade carving, wetland agriculture, and various rock art motifs.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They also share domesticated plants and animals that were carried along with the migrations, including rice, bananas, coconuts, breadfruit, *Dioscorea* yams, taro, paper mulberry, chickens, pigs, and dogs.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The linguistic connections between Madagascar, Polynesia, and Southeast Asia, particularly the similarities between Malagasy, Malay, and Polynesian numerals, were recognized early in the colonial era by European authors.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] German naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster, who traveled with James Cook on his second voyage, also recognized the similarities of Polynesian languages to those of Island Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In his book *Observations Made during a Voyage round the World* (1778), he posited that the ultimate origins of the Polynesians might have been the lowland regions of the Philippines and proposed that they arrived to the islands via long-distance voyaging.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Multiple other authors corroborated this classification (except for the erroneous inclusion of Maldivian), and the language family came to be known as "Malayo-Polynesian", first coined by the German linguist Franz Bopp in 1841 (German: *malayisch-polynesisch*).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The connections between Southeast Asia, Madagascar, and the Pacific Islands were also noted by other European explorers, including the Orientalist William Marsden and the naturalist Johann Reinhold Forster.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Johann Friedrich Blumenbach added Austronesians as the fifth category to his "varieties" of humans in the second edition of *De Generis Humani Varietate Nativa* (1781).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] He initially grouped them by geography and thus called Austronesians the "people from the southern world".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In the third edition, published in 1795, he named Austronesians the "Malay race", or the "brown race", after correspondence with Joseph Banks, who was part of the first voyage of James Cook.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Blumenbach used the term "Malay" due to his belief that most Austronesians spoke the "Malay idiom" (i.e., the Austronesian languages), though he inadvertently caused the later confusion of his racial category with the Malay ethnic group.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The other varieties Blumenbach identified were the "Caucasians" (white), "Mongolians" (yellow), "Ethiopians" (black), and "Americans" (red).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Blumenbach's definition of the "Malay" race is largely identical to the modern distribution of the Austronesian peoples, including not only Islander Southeast Asians but also the people of Madagascar and the Pacific Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Although Blumenbach's work was later used in scientific racism, Blumenbach was a monogenist and did not believe the human "varieties" were inherently inferior to each other.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Rather, he believed that the Malay race was a combination of the "Ethiopian" and "Caucasian" varieties.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] — Johann Friedrich Blumenbach,*The anthropological treatises of Johann Friedrich Blumenbach*, translated by Thomas Bendyshe, 1865.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] By the 19th century, however, a classification of Austronesians as being a subset of the "Mongolian" race was favored, as was polygenism.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The British naturalist James Cowles Prichard originally followed Blumenbach by treating Papuans and Indigenous Australians as being descendants of the same stock as Austronesians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] But by his third edition of *Researches into the Physical History of Man* (1836–1847), his work had become more racialized due to the influence of polygenism.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] He classified the peoples of Austronesia into two groups: the "Malayo-Polynesians" (roughly equivalent to the Austronesian peoples) and the "Kelænonesians" (roughly equivalent to the Australo-Melanesians).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] He further subdivided the latter into the "Alfourous" (also "Haraforas" or "Alfoërs", the Native Australians), and the "Pelagian or Oceanic Negroes" (the Melanesians and western Polynesians).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Despite this, he acknowledges that "Malayo-Polynesians" and "Pelagian Negroes" had "remarkable characters in common", particularly in terms of language and craniometry.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In linguistics, the Malayo-Polynesian language family also initially excluded Melanesia and Micronesia, due to the perceived physical differences between the inhabitants of these regions from Malayo-Polynesian speakers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] However, there was growing evidence of their linguistic relationship to Malayo-Polynesian languages, notably from studies on the Melanesian languages by Georg von der Gabelentz, Robert Henry Codrington, and Sidney Herbert Ray.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Codrington coined and used the term "Ocean" language family rather than "Malayo-Polynesian" in 1891, in opposition to the exclusion of Melanesian and Micronesian languages.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] This was adopted by Ray, who defined the "Oceanic" language family as encompassing the languages of Southeast Asia and Madagascar, Micronesia, Melanesia, and Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In 1899, the Austrian linguist and ethnologist Wilhelm Schmidt coined the term "Austronesian" (German: *austronesisch*, from Latin *auster*, "south wind"; and Greek *νῆσος*, "island") to refer to the language family.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Schmidt had the same motivations as Codrington: he proposed the term as a replacement to "Malayo-Polynesian", because he also opposed the implied exclusion of the languages of Melanesia and Micronesia in the latter name.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] It became the accepted name for the language family, with Oceanic and Malayo-Polynesian languages being retained as names for subgroups.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The term "Austronesian", or more accurately "Austronesian-speaking peoples", came to refer to people who speak the languages of the Austronesian language family.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Some authors, however, object to the use of the term to refer to people, as they question whether there really is any biological or cultural shared ancestry between all Austronesian-speaking groups.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] This is especially true for authors who reject the prevailing "Out of Taiwan" hypothesis and instead offer scenarios where the Austronesian languages spread among preexisting static populations through borrowing or convergence, with little or no population movements.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Despite these objections, the general consensus is that the archeological, cultural, genetic, and especially linguistic evidence all separately indicate varying degrees of shared ancestry among Austronesian-speaking peoples that justifies their treatment as a "phylogenetic unit".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] This has led to the use of the term "Austronesian" in academic literature to refer not only to the Austronesian languages but also the Austronesian-speaking peoples, their societies, and the geographic area of Austronesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Some Austronesian-speaking groups are not direct descendants of Austronesians and acquired their languages through language shift, but this is believed to have happened only in a few instances, since the Austronesian expansion was too rapid for language shifts to have occurred fast enough.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In parts of Island Melanesia, migrations and paternal admixture from Papuan groups after the Austronesian expansion (estimated to have started at around 500 BCE) also resulted in gradual population turnover.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These secondary migrations were incremental and happened gradually enough that the culture and language of these groups remained Austronesian, even though in modern times, they are genetically more Papuan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In the vast majority of cases, the language and material culture of Austronesian-speaking groups descend directly through generational continuity, especially in islands that were previously uninhabited.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Serious research into the Austronesian languages and its speakers has been ongoing since the 19th century.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Modern scholarship on Austronesian dispersion models is generally credited to two influential papers in the late 20th century: *The Colonization of the Pacific: A Genetic Trail* (Hill & Serjeantson, eds., 1989) and *The Austronesian Dispersal and the Origin of Languages* (Bellwood, 1991).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The topic is particularly interesting to scientists for the remarkably unique characteristics of the Austronesian speakers: their extent, diversity, and rapid dispersal.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Regardless, certain disagreements still exist among researchers with regards to chronology, origin, dispersal, adaptations to the island environments, interactions with preexisting populations in areas they settled, and cultural developments over time.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The mainstream accepted hypothesis is the "Out of Taiwan" model first proposed by Peter Bellwood.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] But there are multiple rival models that create a sort of "pseudo-competition" among their supporters due to narrow focus on data from limited geographic areas or disciplines.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The most notable of which is the "Out of Sundaland" (or "Out of Island Southeast Asia") model.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Austronesians were the first humans with seafaring vessels that could cross large distances on the open ocean; this technology allowed them to colonize a large part of the Indo-Pacific region.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Prior to the 16th-century colonial era, the Austronesian language family was the most widespread in the world, spanning half the planet from Easter Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean to Madagascar in the western Indian Ocean.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Languages of the Austronesian family are today spoken by about 386 million people (4.9% of the global population), making it the fifth-largest language family by number of speakers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Major Austronesian languages include Malay (around 250–270 million in Indonesia alone in its own literary standard, named Indonesian), Javanese, and Filipino (Tagalog).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The family contains 1,257 languages, the second-largest number of any language family.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The geographic region that encompasses native Austronesian-speaking populations is sometimes referred to as "Austronesia".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In Indonesia, the nationalistic term Nusantara, from Old Javanese, is also popularly used for the Indonesian islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Austronesian regions are almost exclusively islands in the Pacific and Indian oceans, with predominantly tropical or subtropical climates with considerable seasonal rainfall.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Inhabitants of these regions include Taiwanese indigenous peoples, most ethnic groups in Brunei, East Timor, Indonesia, Madagascar, Malaysia, Micronesia, the Philippines, and Polynesia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Also included are the Malays of Singapore; the Polynesians of New Zealand, Hawaii, and Chile; the Torres Strait Islanders of Australia; the non-Papuan peoples of Melanesia and coastal New Guinea; the Shibushi speakers of Mayotte, and the Malagasy and Shibushi speakers of Réunion.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Austronesians are also found in the regions of Southern Thailand; the Cham areas in Vietnam, Cambodia, and Hainan; and the Mergui Archipelago of Myanmar.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Additionally, modern-era migration has brought Austronesian-speaking people to the United States, Canada, Australia, the UK, mainland Europe, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Suriname, Hong Kong, Macau, and West Asian countries.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Some authors also propose further settlements and contacts in the past in areas that are not inhabited by Austronesian speakers today.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These range from likely hypotheses to very controversial claims with minimal evidence.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In 2009, Roger Blench compiled an expanded map of Austronesia that encompassed these claims based on a variety of evidence, such as historical accounts, loanwords, introduced plants and animals, genetics, archeological sites, and material culture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They include areas like the Pacific coast of the Americas, Japan, the Yaeyama Islands, the Australian coast, Sri Lanka and coastal South Asia, the Persian Gulf, some Indian Ocean islands, East Africa, South Africa, and West Africa.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Austronesians also mixed with other preexisting populations as well as later migrant populations among the islands they settled, resulting in further genetic input.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The most notable are the Austroasiatic-speaking peoples in western Island Southeast Asia (peninsular Malaysia, Sumatra, Borneo, and Java); the Bantu peoples in Madagascar; as well as Japanese, Persian, Indian, Arab, and Han Chinese traders and migrants in more recent centuries.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Island Southeast Asia was settled by modern humans in the Paleolithic following coastal migration routes, presumably starting before 70,000 BP from Africa, long before the development of Austronesian cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These populations are typified by having dark skin, curly hair, and short statures, leading Europeans to believe, in the 19th century, that they were related to African Pygmies.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] However, despite these physical similarities, genetic studies have shown that they are more closely related to other Eurasian populations than to Africans.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The lowered sea levels of the Pleistocene made some of the modern-day islands of Sundaland accessible via land bridges.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] However, the spread of humans across the Wallace line and into Sahul necessitated crossing bodies of water.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Remains of stone tools and marine shells in Liang Sarru, Salibabu Island, North Sulawesi, dated to 32,000–35,000 years ago, is possible evidence for the longest sea voyage by Paleolithic humans ever recorded.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The island was previously uninhabited by humans or hominins and can only be reached from either Mindanao or the Sangihe Islands by crossing an expanse of water at least 100 km (62 mi) wide, even during the low sea levels of the Pleistocene.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Other evidence of early maritime transport are the appearance of obsidian tools with the same source on neighboring islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These include the Philippine obsidian network (Mindoro and Palawan, ca.33,000-28,000 BP), and the Wallacea obsidian network (Timor, Atauro, Kisar, Alor, ca.22,000 BP).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] However, the method of crossing remains unknown and could have ranged from simple rafts to dugout canoes by the terminal Pleistocene.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These early settlers are generally historically referred to as "Australo-Melanesians", though the terminology is problematic, as they are genetically diverse, and most groups within Austronesia have significant Austronesian admixture and culture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The unmixed descendants of these groups today include the interior Papuans and Indigenous Australians.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In modern literature, descendants of these groups, located in Island Southeast Asia west of Halmahera, are usually collectively referred to as "Negritos", while descendants of these groups east of Halmahera (excluding Indigenous Australians) are referred to as "Papuans".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They can also be divided into two broad groups based on Denisovan admixture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Philippine Negritos, Papuans, Melanesians, and Indigenous Australians display Denisovan admixture, while Malaysian and western Indonesian Negritos (Orang Asli) and Andamanese islanders do not.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Mahdi (2017) also uses the term "Qata" (from Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *qata) to distinguish the indigenous populations of Southeast Asia, versus "Tau" (from Proto-Austronesian *Cau) for the later settlers from Taiwan and mainland China.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Both are based on proto-forms for the word "person" in Malayo-Polynesian languages that referred to darker-skinned and lighter-skinned groups, respectively.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Jinam *et al.* (2017) also proposed the term "First Sundaland People" in place of "Negrito", as a more accurate name for the original population of Southeast Asia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These populations are genetically distinct from later Austronesians, but through fairly extensive population admixture, most modern Austronesians have varying levels of ancestry from these groups.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The same is true for some populations historically considered "non-Austronesians", due to physical differences—like Philippine Negritos, Orang Asli, and Austronesian-speaking Melanesians, all of whom have Austronesian admixture.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] In Polynesians in Remote Oceania, for example, the admixture is around 20 to 30% Papuan and 70 to 80% Austronesian.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The Melanesians in Near Oceania are roughly around 20% Austronesian and 80% Papuan, while in the natives of the Lesser Sunda Islands, the admixture is around 50% Austronesian and 50% Papuan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Similarly, in the Philippines, the groups traditionally considered to be "Negrito" vary between 30 and 50% Austronesian.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The high degree of assimilation among Austronesian, Negrito, and Papuan groups indicates that the Austronesian expansion was largely peaceful.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Rather than violent displacement, the settlers and the indigenous groups absorbed each other.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] It is believed that in some cases, like in the Toalean culture of Sulawesi (c.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] 8,000–1,500 BP), it is even more accurate to say that the densely populated indigenous hunter-gatherer groups absorbed the incoming Austronesian farmers, rather than the other way around.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Mahdi (2016) further asserts that Proto-Malayo-Polynesian *tau-mata ("person") is derived from a composite protoform *Cau ma-qata, combining "Tau" and "Qata" and indicative of the mixing of the two ancestral population types in these regions.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The broad consensus on the Urheimat (homeland) of Austronesian languages as well as the Neolithic early Austronesian peoples is accepted to be Taiwan, as well as the Penghu Islands.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They are believed to have descended from ancestral populations in coastal mainland southern China, which are generally referred to as the "pre‑Austronesians".
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Through these pre-Austronesians, Austronesians may also share a common ancestry with neighboring groups in Neolithic southern China.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These Neolithic pre-Austronesians from the coast of southeastern China are believed to have migrated to Taiwan between approximately 10,000 and 6000 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Other research has suggested that, according to radiocarbon dates, Austronesians may have migrated from mainland China to Taiwan as late as 4000 BCE (Dapenkeng culture).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They continued to maintain regular contact with the mainland until 1500 BCE.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The identity of the Neolithic pre-Austronesian cultures in China is contentious.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Tracing Austronesian prehistory in Fujian and Taiwan has been difficult due to the southward expansion of the Han dynasty (2nd century BCE) and the recent Qing dynasty annexation of Taiwan (1683 CE).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Today, the only Austronesian language in southern China is Tsat, spoken in Hainan.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The politicization of archaeology is also problematic, particularly erroneous reconstructions among some Chinese archaeologists of non-Sinitic sites as Han.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Some authors, favoring the "Out of Sundaland" model, like William Meacham, reject the southern Chinese mainland origin of pre-Austronesians entirely.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Nevertheless, based on linguistic, archaeological, and genetic evidence, Austronesians are most strongly associated with the early farming cultures of the Yangtze River basin that domesticated rice from around 13,500 to 8,200 BP.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They display typical Austronesian technological hallmarks, including tooth removal, teeth blackening, jade carving, tattooing, stilt houses, advanced boatbuilding, aquaculture, wetland agriculture, and the domestication of dogs, pigs, and chickens.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These include the Kuahuqiao, Hemudu, Majiabang, Songze, Liangzhu, and Dapenkeng cultures that occupied the coastal regions between the Yangtze River delta and the Min River delta.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Based on linguistic evidence, there have been proposals linking Austronesians with other linguistic families into linguistic macrofamilies that are relevant to the identity of the pre-Austronesian populations.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] The most notable are the connections of Austronesians to the neighboring Austroasiatic, Kra-Dai, and Sinitic peoples (as Austric, Austro-Tai, and Sino-Austronesian, respectively).
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These are still not widely accepted, as evidence of these relationships are still tenuous, and the methods used are highly contentious.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Under that view, there was an east–west genetic alignment, resulting from a rice-based population expansion, in the southern part of East Asia: Austroasiatic-Kra-Dai-Austronesian, with unrelated Sino-Tibetan occupying a more northerly tier.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Depending on the author, other hypotheses have also included other language families like Hmong–Mien and even Japanese-Ryukyuan into the larger Austric hypothesis.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] These peoples were assimilated linguistically and culturally by incoming Austronesian peoples in what is now modern-day Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] They propose that the distinctiveness of Kra-Dai (it is tonal and monosyllabic) was the result of linguistic restructuring due to contact with Hmong–Mien and Sinitic cultures.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] Aside from linguistic evidence, Roger Blench has also noted cultural similarities between the two groups, like facial tattooing, tooth removal or ablation, teeth blackening, snake (or dragon) cults, and the multiple-tongued jaw harps shared by the indigenous Taiwanese and Kra-Dai-speakers.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] However, archaeological evidence for this is still sparse.
[src:domesticated-plants-and-animals-of-austronesia/out-of-taiwan-hypothesis-p01] This is believed to be similar to what happened to the Cham people, who were originally Austronesian settlers (likely from Borneo) to southern Vietnam around 2100–1900 BP and had languages similar to Malay.
